ty'''\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = \n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = 248\n| population_total                = 83,756\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = Kalahandia\n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Odia language|Odia]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 766001, 766002\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| area_code                       = 06670\n| registration_plate              = OD-08\n| blank_name_sec1                 = [[UN/LOCODE]]\n| blank_info_sec1                 = IN BWIP\n| website                         = {{URL|kalahandi.nic.in}}\n| footnotes                       = \n| Place                           = \n}}\n[[File:Bhawanipatna City (Drone View).jpg|thumb|Aerial view of Bhawanipatna City]]\n'''Bhawanipatna''' is a city, and district headquarters of the [[Kalahandi district]], in the Indian state of [[Odisha]]. Bhawanipatna is a city of numerous temples dedicated to different deities of Hindu pantheon. It is named after the presiding deity, '''Bhawani-Shankar''' and '''Patnam''' which means place in Odia like \"Padaa\". Bhawanipatna municipality is the administrative head of the city, which is divided into twenty wards with different sub-areas called ''pada'' (pronounced \"padaa\"). Originally, these ''padaas'' were inhabited by people of different communities, but over the last few decades, these padaas have become homogeneous. Bhawanipatna has more than forty-two ''padaas''.[[File:Durga Mandap, Gandhi Chowk, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Durga Mandap, Gandhi Chowk, Bhawanipatna]]\n[[File:Bhawanipatna Palace.jpg|thumb|Kalahandi Palace, Bhawanipatna]]\n\n==Geography and climate==\nBhawanipatna is located at {{coord|19.9|N|83.17|E|}}.<ref>[http://www.fallingrain.com/world/IN/21/Bhawanipatna.html Falling Rain Genomics, Inc - Bhawanipatna]</ref> It has an average elevation of {{convert|248|m|ft|abbr=on}}. Bhawanipatna is located in the centre of large mountains and plateaus. It has eastern ghat mountains in its eastern frontier.\n\n===Climate===\nBhawanipatna has a tropical wet and dry climate, temperatures remain moderate throughout the year, except from March to June, which can be extremely hot. The temperature in April\u2013May sometimes rises above {{Convert|48|C}}. These summer months also have dry and hot winds. In summers, the temperature can also go up to {{Convert|50|C}}. The city receives about {{Convert|1300|mm|}} of rain, mostly in the monsoon season from late June to early October. Winters last from November to January and are mild, although lows can fall to {{Convert|5|C|}}.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{As of|2011}} India [[census]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2011: Data from the 2011 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|work= |publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Bhawanipatna had a population of 69,045 and total including sub-urban of 83,756. Population of Children with age of 0-6 is 7407 which is 10.73% of total population of Bhawanipatna (M). In Bhawanipatna Municipality, Female Sex Ratio is of 945 against state average of 979. Moreover, Child Sex Ratio in Bhawanipatna is around 911 compared to Orissa state average of 941. Literacy rate of Bhawanipatna city is 85.00% higher than state average of 72.87%. In Bhawanipatna, Male literacy is around 90.95% while female literacy rate is 78.72% according to the 2011 census. Out of total population, 23,705 were engaged in work or business activity. Of this 18,666 were males while 5,039 were females. In census survey, worker is defined as person who does business, job, service, and cultivator and labour activity. Of total 23705 working population, 84.55% were engaged in Main Work while 15.45% of total workers were engaged in Marginal Work.\n\n==Language and literature==\nThe language spoken by the people of Kalahandi is the [[Kalahandia]] dialect of [[Odia language|Oriya]], locally known as Kalahandia . Local weekly newspapers such as Arjji and Kalahandi Express publish articles in standard Odia and Kalahandia language. Other languages include Kui, Bhatri (another dialect of Odia), Parji, Bhunjia, spoken by approximately 7000 Bhunjia Adivasis.\n\n==Politics==\nCurrent [[Member of the Legislative Assembly (India)|MLA]] from Bhawanipatna Assembly Constituency is Pradip Naik of [[Bharatiya Janata party|BJP]], who won the seat in State election of 2019. Previous MLA from this seat is Anam Naik<ref>{{cite web |title=Bhawanipatna (Odisha Vidhan Sabha constituency) |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhawanipatna_(Odisha_Vidhan_Sabha_constituency)#2014_Election_Result |website=Wikipedia |publisher=Wikipedia |accessdate=12 March 2020}}</ref>, he won the election in the year 2014. He is from [[Biju Janata Dal]] . Dusmanta Kumar Naik of [[Indian National Congress|INC]  won the seat in State election of 2009. Pradip Kumar Naik of [[Bharatiya Janata Party|BJP]] won the seat in State elections of 2004 and also in 2000 and 1995, Ajit Das of [[Janata Dal|JD]] won this seat in 1990, Bhaktacharan Das of [[Janata Party|JNP]] in 1985, and Dayanidhi Naik who won this seat in 1980 as a candidate of [[Indian National Congress|INC(I)]] and as INC candidate in 1977.<ref>{{cite web\n|url = http://archive.eci.gov.in/March2004/pollupd/ac/states/s18/Partycomp99.htm\n|title = State Elections 2004 - Partywise Comparison for 99-Bhawanipatna Constituency of Odisha\n|publisher = Election Commission of India\n|accessdate = 2008-09-26\n}}{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nBhawanipatna is part of the [[Kalahandi (Lok Sabha constituency)|Kalahandi constituency]],<ref>{{cite web\n |url=http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2000/background/S18/Orissa_AC_Dist_PC.pdf\n |title=Assembly Constituencies - Corresponding Districts and Parliamentary Constituencies of Odisha\n |publisher=Election Commission of India\n |accessdate=2008-09-26\n |url-status=dead\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304184320/http://archive.eci.gov.in/se2000/background/S18/Orissa_AC_Dist_PC.pdf\n |archivedate=2009-03-04\n}}</ref> currently held by [[Arka Keshari Deo]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://india.gov.in/govt/loksabhampbiodata.php?mpcode=3264 |title=Detailed Profile - Shri Arka Keshari Deo - Members of Parliament (Lok Sabha) - Who's Who - Government: National Portal of India |work=india.gov.in |year=2005 |quote=1990-1991: Union Minister of State, Railways |accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref> and before that by his father [[Bikram Keshari Deo]], who was the younger son of Maharaj Pratap Kesari Deo of Kalahandi.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.indiaelections.co.in/lok-sabha-constituencies/Odisha/kalahandi/ |title=Kalahandi &#124; Odisha Lok Sabha Constituency Elections Results 2009 Kalahandi &#124; Odisha MP Elections Results Kalahandi 2009 &#124; Candidate of Kalahandi Lok Sabha |work=indiaelections.co.in |year=2012 |quote=Updated Election Results Details of Kalahandi |accessdate=14 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Tourism==\n\n* '''[[Maa Manikeshwari Mandir]] and [[Chatar jatra]]'''\nThere are two Manikeshwari Mandir located in Kalahandi district of Odisha, one is in Bhawanipatna and other at Thuamal Rampur. The temple is located in the centre of Bhawanipatna. The main deity here is Goddess Manikeshwari. The main devotees are from the fishermen community. During Dussehra festival, animal sacrifice is offered at this temple which is a festival also known as [[Chatar jatra]] where lacs of people gather in the city to get the blessings from their beloved goddess . A film is also documented showing the ritual of animal sacrifice, before Goddess Manikeshwari.\n\n* '''[[Phurlijharan]]'''\n\n[[File:Phurlijharan.JPG|thumb|Phurlijharan Waterfall]]\n\nPhurlijharan is a perennial water fall about {{Convert|30|ft||0|abbr=on|adj=on}} in height and has a special charm of its own. The multi coloured rainbow created by the sunrays falling on the scattered water particles of the fall is an amusing sight to be seen. The evergreen forests around the fall provide ample opportunities to group picnickers.\n\n* '''[[Karlapat Wildlife Sanctuary]]'''\n\nPresent on SH-44 Karlapat Wildlife Sanctuary (Odia: \u0b15\u0b30\u0b4d\u0b32\u0b3e\u0b2a\u0b3e\u0b1f\u0b4d;Hindi: \u0915\u0930\u094d\u0932\u093e\u092a\u093e\u091f\u094d) is a wildlife sanctuary located in Kalahandi district and a very popular tourist attraction of Odisha in India. The sanctuary covers an area of {{Convert|255|km2||abbr=on}}. It lies within the Eastern Highlands moist deciduous forests ecoregion.[3] Major plant communities include mixed deciduous forests and scrublands.It has also high mineral deposit like bauxite and manganese etc.This sanctuary is home to many wildlife species like tiger, leopard, gaur, sambar, nilgai, barking deer, mouse deer, a wide variety of birds and reptiles.\n\n* '''Jakham'''\n\nIt has a wooden guest house.\n[[File:Jakam, Kalahandi.jpg|thumb|Jakam, Kalahandi]]\n\n* '''Rabandara'''\n[[File:Rabandhara Waterfall, Kalahandi.jpg|thumb|Rabandhara Waterfall, Kalahandi]]\nRabandara is a perennial water fall about {{cvt|13|ft|m|0}} in height and has a special charm of its own.\n\n* '''Sospadar Waterfall'''\n\n[[File:Sospadar Waterfall, Kalahandi.jpg|thumb|Sospadar Waterfall, Kalahandi]]\nSospadar is an exotic location for picnic lovers and adventurers.\n\n* '''Gadagada Twin-Waterfall'''\n* '''Zilla Sangrahalaya'''\n\n[[File:District Museum, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|District Museum Bhawanipatna]]\nZilla Sangrahalaya or the District Museum, Bhawanipatna has different artifacts, manuscripts, paintings and many rare items from pre-historic age (Asurgarh coins, Gudahandi paintings etc.) depicting ancient history of Kalahandi Redion.\n\n* '''Permunji'''\n\n[[File:Manikeshwari Temple (Panoramic View).jpg|thumb|Manikeshwari Temple (Panoramic View)]]\n\nPermunji is a nursery situated at the foot of great mountain, a place for picnics. Elephants are commonly seen near the nursery crossing roads.\n\n* '''Hello Point'''\n\nHello Point is a picnic spot and valley view point . It is present on the top of the eastern ghats from where half of the Kalahandi district is visible including Junagarh, Kalampur block etc. One can receive signal from all telecom services for mobile, therefore it is named as Hello Point.\n\n[[File:Indiravati Dam.jpg|thumb|Indiravati Dam]]\n\n<gallery>\nImage:Phurlijharan Entrance.jpg|Phurlijharan Entrance\nImage:Kalahandi Palace, Bhawanipatna.jpg|Kalahandi Palace, Bhawanipatna\nImage:Baringdoro Waterfall.jpg|Baringdoro Waterfall\nImage:Sabha Mandap, RajMahal Kalahandi.jpg|Sabha Mandap, Raj Mahal Kalahandi\nImage:INSIDE kARLAPAT.jpg|Inside Karlapat Wildlife Sanctuary\nFile:Rabandoro Reservoir.jpg|Bhatang Padar Dam Reservoir\nImage:Jakam Road.jpg|SH-44 Jakham Road\nImage:Lakshmi Mandir.PNG|Lakshmi Mandir, Bhawanipatna\nImage:Statue Square Old Photo.jpg|Statue Square (1950s)\nImage:Grand view of Palace.jpg|Grand view of Kalahandi Palace\nFile:Bhawanipatna town aerial view.jpg|Bhawanipatna Aerial View\n</gallery>\n\n{{panorama|image=File:Hello Point Valley View.jpg|height=320|caption=Panoramic View of Hello Point \"Valley View\"|alt=caption=Panoramic View of Hello Point \"Valley View\"}}\n\n==Media and broadcasting==\n\n[[File:Doordarshan Kendra, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Doordarshan Kendra, Bhawanipatna]][[File:All India Radio, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|All India Radio, Bhawanipatna]]\n\n'''* Doordarshan Kendra (DD-6)'''\n\nIt was started as Low Power Transmission on 15 February 1987 and it had been upgraded to High Power Transmission on 20 January 1992. This 10 KW capacity Doordarshan kendra started functioning in 1992 is one of the few HPT centres among Sambalpur, Cuttack in Odisha. Program generating facility (studio) was started on 3 September 2002. Its one of the three Doordarshan Kendras in the state of Odisha other being Sambalpur and Bhubaneshwar. Its studio became operational in 2002. In 2004, it started broadcasting agriculturerelated programmes sponsored by Ministry of Agriculture and simultaneously began broadcasting agriculture programmes in different HPT (high power transmission) centres of KBK region.\n\nBesides this, it also used to produce programmes to promote tribal heritage, culture, drama besides entertainment and awarenessbuilding programmes for the KBK. It was broadcasting agriculture related programmes from 6 pm to 6.30 pm on every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday and local culture and entertainment based programmes from 5.30 pm to 6 pm each Monday and Thursday. During the period from 2005 to 2009, the centre has bagged 10 national awards and five nominee prizes for different programmes produced by it.\n\n'''* All India Radio (Akashwani Bhawanipatna 103 FM)'''\n\nAll India Radio or Akashwani Bhawanipatna started on 30 December 1993 near Naktiguda, outskirt of the city. It has two transmitters 2x100 KW, MW in Belamal near Pastikudi. Frequency of Transmission is 1206&nbsp;kHz, 248 MTs. It has two studios. Sanctioned strength of Radio station in all cadre is 100. No. Of Casual Announcers in the kendra is 56. Composition of originated programmes targets audience programme for Rural, Women Children, Youth & Senior Citizen, Light & Classical Music, Film Music. Broadcasting of programmes are done in Odia, Hindi, and English languages. The broadcasting covers a popuplation of approx. 18,66,000 Lacs from Kalahandi, Nuapada and nearby districts.\nAll India Radio, #Bhawanipatna was started on 30 Dec 1993 at Naktiguda, Bhawanipatna i.e., Transmission and Studio and Radio Station at Belamal is a Relay Tower.\nRecently FM services have been started at AIR station at frequency of 103&nbsp;MHz\n\nPrimary service zone, Kalahandi District and Naupada District.\nThe station has not only popular in its primary zone, rather its audience from the district of Bolangir, Sonepur, Phulbani, Bargarh, Nawrangpur and Rayagara of Orissa and Raigarh district of Chhattisgarh. Moreover, this station serves the districts coming under the capital KBK scheme of the Govt. of India.\n\nTransmission Strength~BEL HMB 140- 2 x 100 KW\nFrequency of Broadcast~1206&nbsp;kHz and 248 mtrs.\nMast Height~ 122 Meters\n\n'''* My Channel (Local Media Group)'''\n\nDigital Cable TV and WiMax provider.\n\n'''* Ortel Cable and Broadband Service'''\n\nDigital Cable TV and Broadband provider.\n\n'''* EM Digital'''\n\n==Festivals==\n{{Travel guide|section|date=November 2017}}[[File:Maa Manikeswari Chatar Jatra, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Chatar Jatra, Bhawanipatna]][[File:Kalahandi Utsav, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Kalahandi Utsav, Bhawanipatna]]\n* '''Dasra (Dasahara)''' : [[Durga Puja|Dasara]] or [[Durga Puja]] is celebrated among [[Hindu]] all over India, but it is very popular in Eastern part of India including [[Odisha]], [[West Bengal]], Assam etc. However, goddess [[Durga]] is known as Shaki (Energy) and most of the goddess based on tribal and Shaki is inspired from goddess Durga. The major goddess of Kalahandi including Manikeswari, Lankeswari, Denteswari, Khameswari, Bhandargharen etc. are seen as a reflection of goddess Durga and most of the major festivals like Chhatar Jatra, Kkandabasha, Budharaja Jatra, etc. are celebrated during Dusra. Dusra is significant in all the Skati Pitha in Kalahandi and is one of the popular festival in the region.\n* '''Kalahandi Utsav \"Ghumura\"''' : It is hosted in Lal Bahadur Shastri stadium\n* '''Diel or Deepawali''' : Also popularly known as [[Diwali]] is celebrated in Kalahandi. But this is getting popular due to immigrant business community mainly from Marwadi community, however, slowly it has entered the local stream.\n* '''Nuakhai''' : This is typically a local festival prevalent in Western Odisha including Kalahandi. It is inspired from harvesting of new crops and historically came from tribal. But now everybody irrespective of caste, creed and religion celebrate it. There are many kinds of Nuakhai according to tribal culture, out of which Dhan (Rice) Nuakhai is most popularly celebrated.\n* The Chhatra Yatra of Goddess Manikeswari of Bhawanipatna, a popular ceremony. (October)\n\n==Market==\n[[File:Bhawanipatna Market.jpg|thumb|Bhawanipatna Market]]{{Travel guide|section|date=November 2017}}\n* ''' Laxmi Bajar'''\n\nThere are several market areas in the city, the biggest one is Laxmi Bajar or Main Market which is at the core of the city. Most of the garment showrooms, costume, jwellery, grocery and fancy shops are found here. Fruits and Vegetables are sold in the inner area of the market mainly near Laxmi Mandir.\n\n* ''' Hatpada'''\n\nHatpada or Weekly Market is situated near Gandhi Pramod Udyaan (park) is a bi-weekly market that takes place on Tuesday and Saturday where traders from different areas come to sell their goods including vegetables, grocery items, masala & spices, metal products (like utensils etc.), animal and their products like milk products, meat, fishes etc.\n\n* '''Mach bazaar'''\n\nIt is located near Ghodaghat bridge where different types of fishes and prawns are sold.\n\n* '''Naktiguda Haat'''\nIt is a small bajar located on NH-26 mainly known for Grocery and Vegetable items.\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:LBS Stadium, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|LBS Stadium, Bhawanipatna]]{{Prose|section|date=November 2017}}\n# Lal Bahadur Sashtri Stadium is the biggest stadium in [[Odisha]] according to the total field area. It is present near the Bhawani Talkies, Old cinema hall. The stadium has held various matches including the Ranji Trophy and the Kalahandi Cup. It is maintained by Kalahandi District Athletic Association. Various sports and athletic training are conducted including Cricket, football, Karate etc. There are also several tennis courts in the stadium.\n# Indoor Stadium (Gymnasium Hall) is present near the LBS Stadium.\n# The Reserve Police Stadium is the home ground of the Odisha Police.\n# The Govt. Autonomous College Field is one of the largest field present as compared to all others in Bhawanipatana.\n# D.I.E.T. Field is one of the biggest groud available in the city used for club cricket, volleyball and football games.\n\n==Entertainment==\n{{Prose|section|date=November 2017}}\n[[File:New Star Cineplex, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|New Star Cineplex, Bhawanipatna]][[File:Bhagirathi Park, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Bhagirathi Park, Bhawanipatna]]\n'''Talkies/Cinema Halls'''\n\n* Bhawani Talkies- It was the oldest cinema hall in the city present near L.B.S. Stadium with UFO technology. (Now Closed).\n* Satyam Cinema- It is the biggest cinema hall in the city with UFO technology and Dolby Digital sound.\n* New Star Cineplex- It is the Largest Multiplex of South-Western Odisha (KBK-South Odisha) with 4 screens (#3D technology) and total seating capacity of 385 with #Mall (New Fashion World), Restaurants, Gaming Zone and many more. It is situated near OMFED plant, SH-16 Raipur road, Bhangabari, Bhawanipatna.\n*Bhagirathi Mall, Second Mall & Multiplex in Bhawanipatna. Multiplex-4 Screen 3D, Sopping Mall, Restaurant (Bhagirathi Chaupaty ), Gaming Zone, I love Kalahandi...It is situated near Satsang Bihar,NH-26 Junagarh Road,Bhawanipatna.\n\n'''Parks and Ecological Gardens'''\n\n* Bhagirathi Park- Present near Shirdi Sai Mandir on SH-44 is a tourist attraction.\n* Gandhi Pramod Udyaan- Situated near Statue Square.\n* Ecological Park- One of the oldest park present on the outskirt of the city on NH-26.\n\n==Education==\n[[File:Government College of Engineering, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Government College of Engineering, Bhawanipatna]][[File:Government Autonomous College, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Government Autonomous College, Bhawanipatna]]{{Prose|section|date=November 2017}}[[File:College of Agriculture, Bhawanipatna (OUAT).jpg|thumb|College of Agriculture, Bhawanipatna (OUAT)]][[File:Government Polytechnic College.jpg|thumb|Government Polytechnic College]]\n\n===Technical colleges/institutions===\n# [[College of Agriculture, Bhawanipatna]]\n# [[Government College of Engineering, Kalahandi]] Bhawanipatna\n# Government Polytechnic College Bhawanipatna\n\n===General degree colleges===\n# Binayak Residential college, Bhawanipatna\n# [[Government Autonomous College, Bhawanipatna]]\n# Government Women's College Bhawanipatna\n# Jayaprakash Sandhya Mahavidyalaya, Bhawanipatna\n# Pragati Degree College, Bhawanipatna\n# Saraswati Degree College, Bhawanipatna\n# Sastriji Science College, Bhawanipatna\n\n===Schools===\n# Hi-Tech Public School Bhwanipatna\n# Citizens' Model English Medium Academy, Bhawanipatna\n# B.M. High School\n# Delhi Public Kids & Primary School, Bhawanipatna\n# Kendriya Vidyalaya, Bhawanipatna\n# Manikeshwari High School\n# Saraswati Sishu Vidya Mandir\n# Satya Sai Vidya Mandir\n# '''Shastriji model school.(English Medium)'''\n# '''Shastriji Siksha Niketan. (Odia Medium)'''\n# Vimala Convent School\n\n===Computer Institutions===\n# CROWN IT & MANAGEMENT, Mahavirpada, Near Maa Medical Store, Bhawanipatna\n# NICE - National Institute of Computer Education.\n\n==Health care==\n{{Prose|section|date=November 2017}}[[File:District Headquarters Hospital, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|District Headquarters Hospital, Bhawanipatna]]\n[[File:Bhawanipatna Roads (State Highway-44).jpg|thumb|Bhawanipatna Roads]]\nThere is a medical college and several hospitals including nursing homes in the city which provide good health care services in the city.\nThere are many ambulance services like National Ambulance Service (dial 102,108), Janani Express running for health services.\nRecently State Government has announced a government Medical College in Kalahandi. In response 40 acres of land has been handed over to State Health Dept. for the infrastructure development in Bhangabari which is behind Bhawanipatna Ring Road (Proposed). It is adjacent to SH-16 (Proposed NH).\n* '''Kalahandi Medical College & Hospital, Bhangabari, Bhawanipatna'''\n\nState Government had signed with Vedanta Group to build a Medical College and 500 bedded Hospital at Bhangabari near Bhawanipatna. Recently MoU has been signed by State Government and Vedanta Group and land acquisition has been done and soon the work is going to be started.\n\n* '''Sardar Rajas Medical College, Hospital & Research Centre (SRMCH)'''\n\nSRMCH is located {{Convert|17|km||abbr=on}} away from Bhawanipatna on NH-26, it was the only medical college in KBK region earlier enhancing health services in the region. It was established in 2009 with support from WODC and Government of Odisha for conducting Under-graduate Medical Courses.It is a self-financing medical institution with 100 seats. Its now abandoned and case is currently going on by the medical students against Sylvian Trust at Odisha High Court.\n\n* '''District Headquarter Hospital'''\n\nDistrict Headquarter Hospital is the main backbone for the health services in the city and whole district. It has many wards for different kind of patients, there's also a Radio Therapy and Regional Diagnostic centre in the hospital. There is also a blood bank in the hospital campus. Currently a new 6-storey hospital building is under construction.\n\n* '''Maa Manikeswari Multispeciality Hospital'''\n\nEarlier known as Life Worth Hospital it was established in 2004 at Bhawanipatna located near Ghodaghat Chowk (SH-16). It was a branch of Life Worth Super Specialty Hospital present at Raipur. Later it was renamed as Maa Manikeswari Multispeciality Hospital at Bhawanipatna is having all the necessary facilities required during emergency.\n\n* '''Police Hospital'''\nSituated in Armed Reserve Police Campus near College Chowk, Bhawanipatna.\n\n'''Nursing Homes'''\n* Balaji Nursing Home\nNear Balaji Mandir\nPardeshi Para\nBhawanipatna\n\n* Surakhya Nursing Home\nNear Red Cross Kalyan Mandap\nBhawanipatna\n\n* Jagannath Netralaya Eye Hospital\nNear Balaji Mandir\nPardeshi Para\nBhawanipatna\n\n==Transport==\n===Air===\n[[File:Utkela Airstrip, Kalahandi.jpg|thumb|Utkela Airstrip, Kalahandi]]\n[[Utkela Airstrip]] (VEUK) is present near the city ({{Convert|22|km||abbr=on|disp=comma}}) which is scheduled to be operational with daily flights to state capital [[Bhubaneshwar]] and [[Raipur]] in the coming month of September by private air service provider [[Air Odisha]] under [[UDAN]] scheme by Ministry of Civil Aviation, Govt. of India.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/regional-connectivity-gets-wings-five-airlines-get-to-fly-128-routes/article9607388.ece | title=Regional connectivity gets wings; five airlines get to fly 128 routes | newspaper=The Hindu Business Line | first=Ashwini | last=Phadnis | date=15 January 2018 | accessdate=20 January 2019 }}</ref> Another one, [[Lanjigarh Airstrip]] ({{Convert|58|km||abbr=on|disp=comma}}) is private airstrip conducting VIP and chartered planes. Other nearby Airport are Swami Vivekananda Airport at Raipur, Chhattisgarh is {{Convert|262|km||abbr=on}} away. Biju Patnaik International Airport in the state capital, Bhubaneswar is 427&nbsp;km away by road and 631&nbsp;km by rail.\n\n===Rail===\n{{main|Bhawanipatna railway station}}\n[[File:Bhawanipatna Railway.png|thumb|Bhawanipatna Railway Station]]\nBhawanipatna railway station was inaugurated on 12 August 2012.<ref>{{cite web|last=News |first=Express |url=http://newindianexpress.com/states/odisha/article587845.ece |title=Bhawanipatna railway station opens |publisher=The New Indian Express |date= |accessdate=2013-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eastcoastrail.indianrailways.gov.in/view_detail.jsp?lang=0&dcd=709&id=0,4,268 |title=East Coast Railway |publisher=Eastcoastrail.indianrailways.gov.in |date=2012-08-12 |accessdate=2013-05-22}}</ref> It is situated on Lanjigarh-Junagarh rail line. Currently there are 3 trains (1 express and 2 passengers) running from Bhawanipatna to Bhubanneshwar, Raipur and Sambalpur.kesinga Railway station is connected by many major cities in India,like Delhi,Mumbai, Chennai,Surat etc.\n\n===Road===\n[[File:Government Bus Stand, Bhawanipatna (OSRTC).jpg|thumb|Government Bus Stand, Bhawanipatna (OSRTC)]][[File:Old Bus Stand, Bhawanipatna.jpg|thumb|Old Bus Stand, Bhawanipatna]]\nHighways connecting Bhawanipatna to various cities :\n*NH-26 - [[Bargarh]] - [[Bolangir]] - Bhawanipatna - [[Nabarangpur]] - [[Koraput]] - [[Vizianagram]] - [[Natavalsa]]\n*SH-16 -  Bhawanipatna - [[Borda, Odisha|Borda]] - [[Khariar]] - Raipur\n*SH-6 -  Bhawanipatna - [[Chatiguda]] - [[Ambodala]] - [[Muniguda]]\n*SH-44 - Bhawanipatna - [[Gunupur]] - [[Thuamul Rampur]] - [[Kashipur, Odisha|Kashipur]] - [[Tikri, Odisha|Tikri]]\n\nBhawanipatna Bus Stand is one of the biggest bus stand in Odisha present on NH-26. Both Private and Govt. buses are available from here. Bhawanipatna is one of the division of Odisha State Road Transport Corporation (O.S.R.T.C.) that runs Govt. Buses from Bhawanipatna to [[Bhubaneshwar]], [[Vishakhapatnam]], [[Sambalpur]], [[Berhampur]], [[Cuttack]], [[Jeypore]]. Private Buses (A/C Sleeper Coaches) provide transportation facility to different cities in [[Odisha]] and [[Raipur]], [[Durg]] etc. in Chhattisgarh. Newly added taxi facility and auto facility including Biju Gaon Gadi throughout Bhawanipatna and villages nearer to it, is adding an advantage to the transport facility.\n<gallery>\nImage:SH-44.jpg|Hill Town Road (SH-44)\nImage:Statue Square, Bhawanipatna.jpg|Statue Square, Bhawanipatna\nImage:College Square, Bhawanipatna.jpg|College Square, Bhawanipatna\nImage:Gandhi Park Road, BPT.jpg|Gandhi Park Road, BPT\nImage:Stadium Road, BPT.jpg|Stadium Road, BPT\n</gallery>\n\n==Notable personalities==\n* [[Rindo Majhi]]: A freedom fighter in [[Odisha]], who started the Kondha revolution against the British in 1853.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">D.K. Joshi, S. Mund, M.P.Mishra, The Kandha Revolution in Kalahandi, Orissa Review, Aug 2007</ref>\n* [[Bhubaneswar Behera]]: Engineer, academic, administrator and author.<ref>{{cite web |author=Sambit Misra |url=http://www.odiya.org/personality/perslink/bbehera.html |title=Professor Bhubaneswar Behera |publisher=Odiya.org |date=2001-04-25 |accessdate=2013-05-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924054808/http://www.odiya.org/personality/perslink/bbehera.html |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Ram Chandra Patra]], IAS (retd.): (1919-2013) [[Bureaucrat]], social worker, and administrator acknowledged for his simplicity and administration, and for taking initiative in the [[Indravati]] project.<ref>Samabad, 2000</ref><ref>Keun Mahatabanak Pain, Gana nath Das, The Prajatantra, 2 January 1988</ref> He was the first IAS from Kalahandi.\n* Prafulla Ratha: Awarded a natyarashmi for his contribution to Oriya drama.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.airbpn.org/about.htm |title=Akashvani, Bhawanipatna - Home |publisher=Airbpn.org |accessdate=2013-05-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20120802091308/http://www.airbpn.org/about.htm |archivedate=2012-08-02 }}</ref>\n* [[Kishen Pattanayak|Kishan Patnaik]]: Socialist leader.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cpiml.org/liberation/year_2004/November/obituary.htm |title=Obituary |publisher=Cpiml.org |date=2004-10-08 |accessdate=2013-05-22 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130525002428/http://www.cpiml.org/liberation/year_2004/November/obituary.htm |archivedate=2013-05-25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://archive.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/sep272004/update2.asp |title=Socialist leader Kishan Patnaik dead - Deccan Herald |publisher=Archive.deccanherald.com |date=2004-09-27 |accessdate=2013-05-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925050906/http://archive.deccanherald.com/deccanherald/sep272004/update2.asp |archive-date=25 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> He was born in 1930 into a lower-middle-class family in Kalahandi. Mr Patnaik worked in the youth wing of Samajwadi Yuvjan Sabha and soon rose to become its National president. He was elected to Lok Sabha from Sambalpur at the age of 32 and was one of handful members who turned the Lok Sabha into a real forum to discuss matters of national importance. He was perhaps the first person to bring the issue of starvation death in Kalahandi to the Indian parliament. Mr. Patnaik never lost sight of this fundamental plight of rural India, and securing the right to livelihood for the people on the margin therefore always remained central to his politics and to his vision of development.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.hindu.com/2004/09/30/stories/2004093001380300.htm | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | title=Kishan Patnaik remembered | date=30 September 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Power and transmission==\nThere is a 132/33 kV Grid Station near [[OMFED]] diary on SH-16. Power to this grid comes directly from [[Therubali]] Grid.\nPower transmission and maintenance is done by [[Grid Corporation of Odisha]].\n\nThere is also a sub-station in Naktiguda, Bhawanipatna. It is maintained by [[Western Electricity Supply Company of Odisha]]\n\n[[File:Sunset at Hilltown.jpg|thumb|Sunset at Hilltown]]\n[[File:Bpt.png|thumb|NH BYPASS AND RING ROADS, BHAWANIPATNA]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://kalahandi.nic.in/ Official website of Kalahandi]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060904090411/http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/orissa/districts/kalahandi.htm Map of Kalahandi]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Bhawanipatna\n|North     = [[Kesinga]], [[Sambalpur]]\n|Northeast = [[Madanpur Rampur]], [[Phulbani]]\n|East      = [[Narla]]\n|Southeast = [[Rayagada]]\n|South     = [[Thuamul Rampur]], [[Koraput]]\n|Southwest = [[Nabarangpur]], [[Jeypore]]\n|West      = [[Junagarh, Kalahandi|Junagarh]], [[Dharamgarh]]\n|Northwest = [[Khariar]], [[Raipur]]\n}}\n{{Kalahandi district}}\n{{Municipalities of Odisha}}\n{{Western Odisha}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Kalahandi district]]\n", "name_user": "Divyam Seth", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitics", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhawanipatna"}
{"title_page": "Masjchun Sofwan", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Masjchun Sofwan\n|image           = Masjchun Sofwan.jpg\n|office          = Governor of [[Jambi]]\n|term_start      = 1979\n|term_end        = 1989\n|predecessor     = {{interlanguage link|Eddy Sabara|id}}\n|successor       = {{interlanguage link|Abdurrahman Sayoeti|id}}\n|birth_date      = 7 September 1927\n|birth_place     = [[Blitar]], [[East Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n|death_date      = {{death date and age|2015|10|3|1927|9|7|df=y}}\n|death_place     = [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n|education       = \n|occupation      = \n|profession      = \n|website         = \n}}\n\n'''Masjchun Sofwan''' (7 September 1927 \u2013 3 October 2015) was the governor of [[Jambi]] from 1979 to 1989. After graduating from [[Gadjah Mada University]], Sofwan served as the mayor of the [[Temanggung Regency]] from 1964 until 1978. He replaced [[Eddy Sabara]] as the governor of the province.<ref>{{cite news |title=Masjchun Sofwan; Tertantang Jalan Kubangan Kerbau |url=http://jambi.tribunnews.com/2015/01/06/masjchun-sofwan-tertantang-jalan-kubangan-kerbau |accessdate=30 September 2018 |work=Tribun Jambi |date=6 January 2015 |language=id-ID}}</ref>\n\nHe died on 3 October 2015 in Jakarta due to complications from a disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mantan Gubernur Jambi Masjchun Sofwan Berpulang |url=http://jambi.tribunnews.com/2015/10/04/mantan-gubernur-jambi-masjchun-sofwan-berpulang |accessdate=30 September 2018 |work=Tribun Jambi |date=4 October 2015 |language=id-ID}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sofwan, Masjchun}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Governors of Jambi]]\n[[Category:People from Blitar]]\n[[Category:Gadjah Mada University alumni]]\n[[Category:Regents of Temanggung]]\n\n\n{{Indonesia-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=October 2015}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name            = Masjchun Sofwan\n|image           = Masjchun Sofwan.jpg\n|office          = Governor of [[Jambi]]\n|term_start      = 1979\n|term_end        = 1989\n|predecessor     = {{interlanguage link|Eddy Sabara|id}}\n|successor       = {{interlanguage link|Abdurrahman Sayoeti|id}}\n|birth_date      = 7 September 1927\n|birth_place     = [[Blitar]], [[East Java]], [[Indonesia]]\n|death_date      = {{death date and age|2015|10|3|1927|9|7|df=y}}\n|death_place     = [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n|education       = \n|occupation      = \n|profession      = \n|website         = \n}}\n\n'''Masjchun Sofwan''' (7 September 1927 \u2013 3 October 2015) was the governor of [[Jambi]] from 1979 to 1989. After graduating from [[Gadjah Mada University]], Sofwan served as the mayor of the [[Temanggung Regency]] from 1964 until 1978. He replaced Eddy Sabara as the governor of the province.<ref>{{cite news |title=Masjchun Sofwan; Tertantang Jalan Kubangan Kerbau |url=http://jambi.tribunnews.com/2015/01/06/masjchun-sofwan-tertantang-jalan-kubangan-kerbau |accessdate=30 September 2018 |work=Tribun Jambi |date=6 January 2015 |language=id-ID}}</ref>\n\nHe died on 3 October 2015 in Jakarta due to complications from a disease.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mantan Gubernur Jambi Masjchun Sofwan Berpulang |url=http://jambi.tribunnews.com/2015/10/04/mantan-gubernur-jambi-masjchun-sofwan-berpulang |accessdate=30 September 2018 |work=Tribun Jambi |date=4 October 2015 |language=id-ID}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sofwan, Masjchun}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2015 deaths]]\n[[Category:Governors of Jambi]]\n[[Category:People from Blitar]]\n[[Category:Gadjah Mada University alumni]]\n[[Category:Regents of Temanggung]]\n\n\n{{Indonesia-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Juxlos", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masjchun_Sofwan"}
{"title_page": "The Metropolis of Tomorrow", "text_new": "{{short description|Book written and illustrated by Hugh Ferriss}}\n{{Infobox book\n| italic title      = <!--(see above)-->\n| name              = The Metropolis of Tomorrow\n| image             = The Metropolis of Tomorrow cover.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| border            = yes\n| alt               = \n| caption           = Modern cover\n| author            = [[Hugh Ferriss]]\n| audio_read_by     = \n| title_orig        = \n| orig_lang_code    = \n| title_working     = \n| translator        = \n| illustrator       = Hugh Ferriss\n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| series            = \n| release_number    = \n| subject           = [[Architecture]], [[futures studies|futurology]]\n| genre             = Non-fiction\n| set_in            = \n| publisher         = [[Ives Washburn]]\n| publisher2        = \n| pub_date          = 1929\n| english_pub_date  = \n| published         = \n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = \n| awards            = \n| isbn              = 9780910413114 \n| isbn_note         = (1986 edition)\n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource        = \n| notes             = \n| exclude_cover     = \n| website           = \n}}\n\n'''''The Metropolis of Tomorrow''''' is a 1929 book written and illustrated by [[Hugh Ferriss]]. Prominently featuring 60 of Ferriss' drawings, the book is divided into three sections. The first, \"Cities of Today\", underscores the lack of planning in contemporary cities and the powerful psychological impact that cities have on their inhabitants while also profiling 18 influential modern buildings in five cities. The second section, \"Projected Trends\", prominently discusses practical concerns related to [[population density]] and [[traffic congestion]], demonstrates Ferriss' adherence to some of the key elements of [[modern architecture]] (especially [[functionalism (architecture)|functionalism]]), and then analyzes projected trends in urban design that he supports, as well as a few that he opposes. The third and final section, \"An Imaginary Metropolis\", describes an ideal future city complete with towering skyscrapers spaced well apart from each other, broad avenues, and a strongly geometric city layout based around centers and sub-centers of buildings that are segregated by function.\n\nFirst published by [[Ives Washburn]] in 1929, ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' was out of print long before the [[Princeton Architectural Press]] republished it in 1986. Contemporary critical reception to the book was mostly positive and enthusiastic, and generally regarded Ferriss' ideas for the future city as credible and even practical. While in the minority, negative contemporary reviews of the book significantly came mostly from proponents of the [[regional planning]] movement. Writing with the benefit of hindsight in 1986, architectural historian [[Carol Willis (architectural historian)|Carol Willis]] noted the strong connections between the first and second sections of the book (\"Cities of Today\" and \"Projected Trends\"), but criticized the final section (\"An Imaginary Metropolis\") as a flight of fantasy, both impracticable and lacking in nuance. Similarly, more recent reviewers have concentrated on \"An Imaginary Metropolis\", which they generally view as a fantasy which has had a strong influence on later architects and urban planners, and has also been influential to the appearance of futuristic cities in [[comic book]]s and [[film]]s.\n\n== Synopsis ==\n\n=== \"Cities of Today\" ===\n[[File:Print, Proposed Convocation Tower, Madison Square (Northeast Corner of Madison Avenue and East 26th Streeet), 1921 (CH 18452119).jpg|150px|thumb|Hugh Ferriss' drawing of the unbuilt [[Convocation Tower]]]]\n\n''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' is divided into three sections which in total prominently feature 60 of [[Hugh Ferriss]]' drawings.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} The first section, \"Cities of Today\", begins with a vignette describing the contemporary [[New York City]] skyline of the late 1920s in theatrical terms, largely focusing on the enormous scale of modern skyscrapers and the impressions they make on city dwellers.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=15\u201317}} According to architectural historian [[Carol Willis (architectural historian)|Carol Willis]], this section outlines the book's main themes, namely the lack of planning in contemporary cities, the powerful psychological impact that cities have on their inhabitants, and the responsibility of architects to preserve humanistic values as cities continue to grow.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} \"Cities of Today\" is mostly devoted to a brief building-by-building analysis of what Ferriss viewed as \"some of the outstanding buildings of the country\", which he considered especially influential and illustrative of future trends.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=18}} In total, 18 projects by 15 different architectural firms in five cities are examined.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} The first two buildings profiled are both in [[St. Louis]]: the [[Southwestern Bell Building|Telephone Building]], noted for its use of [[setback (architecture)|setbacks]];{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=20}} and the [[St. Louis Plaza]], which Ferriss upheld as an example of collaborative architectural planning that did not compromise design.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=22}} The next two buildings featured are in [[Chicago]], the [[Chicago Board of Trade Building]]{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=24}} and the [[Tribune Tower|Chicago Tribune Building]], the latter of which Ferriss considered unusually beautiful for an office building.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=26}}\n\nFollowing the St. Louis and Chicago projects, the next set of buildings profiled are all in New York City, and Ferriss featured many of them because of their innovative and sometimes controversial design and styling. These buildings include the [[American Radiator Building|Radiator Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=28}} the [[New York Marriott East Side|Shelton Hotel]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=30}} the unbuilt [[Belden Project]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=32}} the [[Master Apartments|Master Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=34}} the [[Waldorf Astoria New York|Waldorf-Astoria Office Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=36}} the lobby of the [[Daily News Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=38}} and the unbuilt [[Convocation Tower]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=40}} Following them are three buildings in [[Detroit]] that Ferriss described as \"undoubtedly the forerunners of the future city\":{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=42}} the [[Penobscot Building|Greater Penobscot Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=42}} the [[Fisher Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=44}} and the [[David Stott Building]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=46}} Following this is a single building in [[Los Angeles]], the [[Los Angeles City Hall|Los Angeles Municipal Tower]], which Ferriss noted was the only true skyscraper in the city at the time due to municipal building height limitations.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=48}}\n\nFerriss concluded the \"Cities of Today\" section by returning to New York City and profiling three recent buildings that were built to unprecedented heights and which were, in Ferriss' opinion, the projects that most foreshadowed future developments in skyscrapers and urban construction more generally.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=50}} To Willis, these were the buildings that \"raised the issues of the race for height and of congestion.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} The three buildings are the [[Chanin Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=50}} the [[Chrysler Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=52}} and the [[40 Wall Street|Bank of the Manhattan Company Building]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=54}}\n\n=== \"Projected Trends\" ===\n[[File:Drawing, Study for Maximum Mass Permitted by the 1916 New York Zoning Law, Stage 4, 1922 (CH 18468717).jpg|150px|thumb|Ferriss' drawing on a study for the maximum mass permitted by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution|1916 New York City zoning laws]]]]\n\nThe second section, \"Projected Trends\", begins with a brief vignette about the \"lure of the city\" to young people and prominently discusses practical concerns related to [[population density]] and [[traffic congestion]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=59}} Almost all of the drawings in this section were published or exhibited prior to being included in ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow''.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=170}} In \"Projected Trends\", Ferriss reveals some of his ideas about the power of architecture to influence human thought and behavior, and he proceeds to espouse some of the key elements of [[modern architecture]], especially [[functionalism (architecture)|functionalism]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=60\u201361}} He also voices his objection to densely crowding numerous skyscrapers in close proximity to each other, as well as his opposition to building roads and bridges for automobiles above street level in city centers, both of which were somewhat popular ideas among [[futurist]]s at the time.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=62\u201364}} According to Willis, these drawings depicting densely packed skyscrapers and elevated automobile traffic have ironically \"often been misread as endorsements, whereas Ferriss conceived them as admonitions.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=170}}\n\nFrom here, Ferriss turns his attention to projected trends that he supports: segregating pedestrians from cars by building a system of arcaded walks along buildings, with bridges across intersections one story over street level;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=66}} building skyscraper churches with either apartments or offices accommodating most of the floors, with the [[sanctuary]] either at the base or the top of the building;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=68}} and [[suspension bridge]]s with apartments built into the side of the [[deck (bridge)|bridge deck]] as well as the bridge towers.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=70}} Willis stresses the serious nature of these proposals, observing that \"in the endless invention and boundless expansion of the 1920s, virtually no scheme seemed impossible.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=170}} Ferriss proceeds to describe and diagram the evolution of the setback principle for skyscraper design, in which he likens the architect's work to a [[sculpture|sculptor]] working with [[clay]], and argues that [[1916 Zoning Resolution|New York City's zoning laws]] are actually a blessing in disguise to architects as they all but mandated the adoption of the setback principle.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=72\u201384}}\n\nFerriss continues with a more practical discussion of the advantages of building skyscrapers on wide avenues and spreading them out from other tall buildings,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=86}} as well as the possibility of constructing buildings spanning two blocks or more with streets passing beneath them in scenic tunnels.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=88\u201390}} He then briefly criticizes architects who wish to revert to \"past styles\" with base-shaft-crown construction instead of adhering to his setback principle{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=92}} before then predicting the increasing popularity of [[penthouse apartment]]s,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=94}} [[roof garden|rooftop gardens]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=96}} and the development of \"modern [[ziggurat]]s\" hosting restaurants and theaters, which he viewed as a natural outgrowth of New York City's zoning laws and setback design.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=98}} Ferriss then concludes the section by noting and extolling the virtues of the three most important building materials for future buildings: [[steel]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=104}} [[concrete]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=102}} and (especially) [[architectural glass|glass]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=100}}\n\n=== \"An Imaginary Metropolis\" ===\nThe third section, \"An Imaginary Metropolis\", begins with a theatrical vignette similar to that of the opening section, but this time the curtain rises on \"a city of the imagination\".{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=109}} It features tall buildings, many of them {{Convert|1,000|ft|m}} in height or taller. Instead of being densely packed, however, they are spread apart from each other and are segregated by function. The tall buildings take up three to eight city blocks for their bases, and they are separated from each other by {{Convert|0.5|mi|km}} of low-rise buildings no taller than six stories in height and connected by broad avenues.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=109\u2013111}} Ferriss visualizes this ideal city as having three main zones: a Business Center, the largest of the three centers, and also home to municipal government buildings;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=112}} an Art Center;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=114}} and a Science Center, which features [[laboratory|laboratories]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=116}} He then outlines the sub-centers of the city, also conceptualized functionally: a Finance Center,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=128}} a Technology Center,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=130}} an Industrial Arts Center,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=132}} and a Philosophy Center.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=136}} These sub-centers are located logically in relation to the centers, so for instance, the Philosophy Center is located between the Art Center and the Science Center.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=171}}\n\nFerriss also sketches plans for a [[fossil fuel power station|coal-fired power plant]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=126}} as well as a single skyscraper church shared by all of the city's religious denominations.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=134}} He visualizes the transportation infrastructure of the city as consisting of underground [[rapid transit|subways]] and [[underground parking|car parking]], with ground-level streets for cars.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=130}} Ferriss concludes the section by providing a bird's eye view of this ideal city, which is centered around a triangular Civic Circle with each of the three main zones (Business Center, Art Center, and Science Center) at its corners, with radial avenues fanning out from them to the sub-centers and ultimately on to the outlying districts of the city.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=138\u2013140}} Willis compares this conception to a [[Renaissance]] treatise, noting its \"strong geometric plan which was primarily formal and symbolic, rather than functional\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=171}} Ferriss concludes the book with a brief epilogue that focuses on his belief about how much architecture influences people.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=142}}\n\n== Publication ==\n[[File:HughFerrissAtWork1925.jpg|thumb|Ferriss at work in 1925]]\n\nFerriss received an advance [[royalty payment|royalty]] of $1,000 from the book's publisher, [[Ives Washburn]], in 1929.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}} The book was published in late 1929, after the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Wall Street crash]].{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=148}} Of the 60 illustrations featured in the book, only 13 of them were created specifically for ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'', and all of these 13 appear in the final section \"An Imaginary Metropolis\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}}\n\nWriting in 1986, architectural historian Carol Willis noted that the book had been \"long out of print\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=149}} In 1986, [[Princeton Architectural Press]] republished ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' (along with an essay by Willis) as a companion to the exhibition ''Hugh Ferriss: Metropolis'', which was sponsored by the [[Architectural League of New York]] and partially supported by a grant from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]]. The exhibit opened at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]] in New York City and then traveled to the [[Walker Art Center]] in [[Minneapolis]], the [[Art Institute of Chicago]], the [[National Building Museum]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the Centre de Cr\u00e9ation Industrielle at the [[Centre Georges Pompidou]] in [[Paris]], and the [[Architectural Association School of Architecture|Architectural Association]] in [[London]].{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=iv}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\nContemporary reception to ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' was mostly positive and enthusiastic, and generally regarded Ferriss' ideas for the future city as credible and even practical.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=174}} Albert Guerard of ''Herald Tribune Books'' called the book \"wise and generous in vision, cogent in thought, clear and strong in literary style, appealing as a work of art, magically stirring as a prophecy\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Tomorrow Seen by Today|last=Guerard|first=Albert|date=January 19, 1930|work=Herald Tribune Books|page=1}}</ref> Joseph G. Niehardt of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' went as far as to declare that he had \"yet to see a book in which the depth of genuine poetic feeling, philosophic grasp and scientific practicality were mysteriously merged.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=On Making Many Books|last=Niehardt|first=John G.|date=December 12, 1929|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times Book Review|New York Times Book Review]]'' critic R. L. Duffus expressed some reservations over the scale and density of Ferriss' vision, but nonetheless assumed the inevitability of further centralization and thus his ordering of the future city: \"Monster cities and buildings are already here. They are being built by forces not yet under our control. The task is to subdue them&nbsp;... [and] Mr. Ferriss has contributed something to the fulfillment of that goal.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Metropolis of the Future: Mr. Ferriss Considers the Problem Created by the Skyscraper|last=Duffus|first=R. L.|date=December 8, 1929|work=[[The New York Times Book Review]]|page=10}}</ref>\n\nNegative contemporary reviews of ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' came mostly from proponents of the [[regional planning]] movement.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=175}} In this vein, Geddes Smith wrote that the book \"is certainly beautiful and is probably vicious&nbsp;... because to glorify the American skyscraper is to confirm the thoughtlessness in a perilous fallacy.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Lovely Monsters|last=Smith|first=Geddes|date=March 15, 1930|work=[[The Survey]]|issue=63|page=727}}</ref> Even more representative of the regional planning movement was the criticism of Regional Plan Association of America member [[Lewis Mumford]],{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=175}} who warned that under Ferriss' proposal \"innumerable human lives will doubtless be sacrificed to Traffic, Commerce, Properly Regulated and Zoned Heights on a scale that will make [[Moloch]] seem an agent of charity.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Sacred City|last=Mumford|first=Lewis|date=January 27, 1926|work=[[The New Republic]]|issue=45|page=271|author-link=Lewis Mumford}}</ref> Mumford further objected to skyscrapers as \"pyramids of ground rents\",<ref>{{Cite news|title=Skyscrapers in the City of the Future|last=Mumford|first=Lewis|date=April 23, 1930|work=[[The New Republic]]|issue=62|page=275|author-link=Lewis Mumford}}</ref> and warned of the seductive nature of Ferriss' vision to professional [[urban planner]]s as well as the general public, arguing that \"this vulgar dream\" was so powerful that \"even the decent and otherwise enlightened technicians of the New York Committee on the Regional Plan have fallen under it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The City of Tomorrow|last=Mumford|first=Lewis|date=February 12, 1930|work=[[The New Republic]]|issue=61|page=332|author-link=Lewis Mumford}}</ref>\n\nWriting in 1986, Carol Willis notes that Ferriss' \"future city seems decidedly a fantasy, exaggerated in its scale and hierarchical order, and certainly impracticable.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=174}} She further writes that with the benefit of \"today's historical distance, the impressive scale and harmonious ensembles of Ferriss' colossal towers and the formal hierarchy of his ideal city seem obviously impracticable and politically naive\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=148}} Furthermore, she observes that Ferriss' \"ideal metropolis radically contradicts most current opinion on the best qualities of a liveable city\", most notably \"an emphasis on pedestrian scale, public spaces, historic preservation and a heterogeneous urban fabric\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=148}} More concretely, Willis notes that while Ferriss detailed some features of the city in great detail, \"many other aspects of urban life were completely ignored\",{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}} including schools, hospitals, police stations, post offices, stadiums, movie theaters, factories, and residences.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}} She observes that while the first two sections of the book \"linked current conditions and future projects\", the third and final section \"presented not an extrapolation or evolution of the contemporary city, but a utopia created ''[[ex novo]]''\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=174}}\n\n[[File:Justin Davidson introduces his book Magnetic City at Columbia GSAPP (cropped).jpg|125px|thumb|[[Justin Davidson]]]]\n\nIn 2016, while writing for ''[[CityLab]]'', [[Carl Abbott (urban historian)|Carl Abbott]] described the \"unrestrained imagination\" of Ferriss that \"created a city of the future in which step-pyramid towers rise from vaguely glimpsed streets\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.citylab.com/life/2016/10/behind-the-urbanism-in-science-fiction/504716/|title=Behind the Urbanism in Science Fiction|last=Abbott|first=Carl|date=October 21, 2016|work=[[CityLab]]|access-date=May 27, 2019|author-link=Carl Abbott (urban historian)}}</ref> In his observation, Ferriss drew \"fantastic views\" filled with \"hypertrophied Chrysler Buildings and superscaled [[Rockefeller Center]]s\".<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2017, Ramona Albert, founder and [[principal (architecture)|principal]] of Ramona Albert Architecture, wrote that in ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'', Ferriss \"offers an eerily accurate depiction of what cities could look like in the future, even though it was written almost a century ago.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.greenbiz.com/article/3-big-ways-sustainable-design-will-shape-future-cities|title=3 big ways sustainable design will shape future cities|last=Albert|first=Ramona|date=May 10, 2017|work=[[GreenBiz]]|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> According to [[Justin Davidson]], writing in 2017 for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, Ferriss \"understood the romance embedded in the new zoning code\" and, in his writing, was able to transform the zoning code into a \"spectacularly utopian tool\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2017/04/nyc-walking-tour-of-42nd-street.html|title=A Walking Tour of 42nd Street|last=Davidson|first=Justin|date=April 2017|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=May 27, 2019|author-link=Justin Davidson}}</ref> Furthermore, he argued that ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow \"''shaped the dreams of architects, planners, comic-book illustrators, and Hollywood set designers.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWriting for ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' in 2018, Darren Garrett argued that the third section of ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' echoed [[Ebenezer Howard]]'s ''[[Garden Cities of To-morrow]]'' while also illustrating Ferriss' \"plans for an entire city that showcases not only his draughtsmanship, but his forward-looking ideas on urban planning\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/quartzy/1342049/weird-and-wonderful-visions-of-the-future-that-never-came-to-pass/|title=Weird and wonderful visions of the future that never came to pass|last=Garrett|first=Darren|date=August 5, 2018|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> He further observed that Ferriss' drawings went beyond simple [[architectural rendering]]s, as \"his dramatic sense of light and shadow depict cities strangely devoid of people, or solo figures dwarfed by their majestic surroundings.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Also in 2018, [[Andrew Berman]] of the [[Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation]] wrote that ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' \"influenced a generation of architects who created some of the most striking and memorable buildings of the era, including the [[Empire State Building|Empire State]] and Chrysler Buildings.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.6sqft.com/from-mark-twain-and-the-lovin-spoonful-to-tech-hub-exploring-the-overlooked-history-of-union-square-south/|title=From Mark Twain and the Lovin' Spoonful to Tech Hub: The overlooked history of Union Square South|last=Berman|first=Andrew|date=December 7, 2018|work=6sqft|access-date=May 27, 2019|author-link=Andrew Berman}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last = Ferriss |first = Hugh |author-link = Hugh Ferriss |title = The Metropolis of Tomorrow |url = https://archive.org/details/mettomo00ferr |date = 1929 |publisher = [[Ives Washburn]] }}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last = Willis |first = Carol |author-link = Carol Willis (architectural historian) |chapter = Drawing Towards Metropolis |title = The Metropolis of Tomorrow |date = 1986 |publisher = [[Princeton Architectural Press]] |isbn = 0-910413-11-8 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metropolis of Tomorrow, The}}\n\n[[Category:1929 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about urbanism]]\n[[Category:Design books]]\n[[Category:Futurology books]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Book written and illustrated by Hugh Ferriss}}\n{{Infobox book\n| italic title      = <!--(see above)-->\n| name              = The Metropolis of Tomorrow\n| image             = The Metropolis of Tomorrow cover.jpg\n| image_size        = \n| border            = yes\n| alt               = \n| caption           = Modern cover\n| author            = [[Hugh Ferriss]]\n| audio_read_by     = \n| title_orig        = \n| orig_lang_code    = \n| title_working     = \n| translator        = \n| illustrator       = Hugh Ferriss\n| cover_artist      = \n| country           = United States\n| language          = English\n| series            = \n| release_number    = \n| subject           = [[Architecture]], [[futures studies|futurology]]\n| genre             = Non-fiction\n| set_in            = \n| publisher         = [[Ives Washburn]]\n| publisher2        = \n| pub_date          = 1929\n| english_pub_date  = \n| published         = \n| media_type        = Print\n| pages             = \n| awards            = \n| isbn              = 9780910413114 \n| isbn_note         = (1986 edition)\n| oclc              = \n| dewey             = \n| congress          = \n| preceded_by       = \n| followed_by       = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource        = \n| notes             = \n| exclude_cover     = \n| website           = \n}}\n\n'''''The Metropolis of Tomorrow''''' is a 1929 book written and illustrated by [[Hugh Ferriss]]. Prominently featuring 60 of Ferriss' drawings, the book is divided into three sections. The first, \"Cities of Today\", underscores the lack of planning in contemporary cities and the powerful psychological impact that cities have on their inhabitants while also profiling 18 influential modern buildings in five cities. The second section, \"Projected Trends\", prominently discusses practical concerns related to [[population density]] and [[traffic congestion]], demonstrates Ferriss' adherence to some of the key elements of [[modern architecture]] (especially [[functionalism (architecture)|functionalism]]), and then analyzes projected trends in urban design that he supports, as well as a few that he opposes. The third and final section, \"An Imaginary Metropolis\", describes an ideal future city complete with towering skyscrapers spaced well apart from each other, broad avenues, and a strongly geometric city layout based around centers and sub-centers of buildings that are segregated by function.\n\nFirst published by [[Ives Washburn]] in 1929, ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' was out of print long before the [[Princeton Architectural Press]] republished it in 1986. Contemporary critical reception to the book was mostly positive and enthusiastic, and generally regarded Ferriss' ideas for the future city as credible and even practical. While in the minority, negative contemporary reviews of the book significantly came mostly from proponents of the [[regional planning]] movement. Writing with the benefit of hindsight in 1986, architectural historian [[Carol Willis (architectural historian)|Carol Willis]] noted the strong connections between the first and second sections of the book (\"Cities of Today\" and \"Projected Trends\"), but criticized the final section (\"An Imaginary Metropolis\") as a flight of fantasy, both impracticable and lacking in nuance. Similarly, more recent reviewers have concentrated on \"An Imaginary Metropolis\", which they generally view as a fantasy which has had a strong influence on later architects and urban planners, and has also been influential to the appearance of futuristic cities in [[comic book]]s and [[film]]s.\n\n== Synopsis ==\n\n=== \"Cities of Today\" ===\n[[File:Print, Proposed Convocation Tower, Madison Square (Northeast Corner of Madison Avenue and East 26th Streeet), 1921 (CH 18452119).jpg|150px|thumb|Hugh Ferriss' drawing of the unbuilt [[Convocation Tower]]]]\n\n''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' is divided into three sections which in total prominently feature 60 of [[Hugh Ferriss]]' drawings.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} The first section, \"Cities of Today\", begins with a vignette describing the contemporary [[New York City]] skyline of the late 1920s in theatrical terms, largely focusing on the enormous scale of modern skyscrapers and the impressions they make on city dwellers.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=15\u201317}} According to architectural historian [[Carol Willis (architectural historian)|Carol Willis]], this section outlines the book's main themes, namely the lack of planning in contemporary cities, the powerful psychological impact that cities have on their inhabitants, and the responsibility of architects to preserve humanistic values as cities continue to grow.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} \"Cities of Today\" is mostly devoted to a brief building-by-building analysis of what Ferriss viewed as \"some of the outstanding buildings of the country\", which he considered especially influential and illustrative of future trends.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=18}} In total, 18 projects by 15 different architectural firms in five cities are examined.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} The first two buildings profiled are both in [[St. Louis]]: the [[Southwestern Bell Building|Telephone Building]], noted for its use of [[setback (architecture)|setbacks]];{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=20}} and the [[St. Louis Plaza]], which Ferriss upheld as an example of collaborative architectural planning that did not compromise design.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=22}} The next two buildings featured are in [[Chicago]], the [[Chicago Board of Trade Building]]{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=24}} and the [[Tribune Tower|Chicago Tribune Building]], the latter of which Ferriss considered unusually beautiful for an office building.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=26}}\n\nFollowing the St. Louis and Chicago projects, the next set of buildings profiled are all in New York City, and Ferriss featured many of them because of their innovative and sometimes controversial design and styling. These buildings include the [[American Radiator Building|Radiator Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=28}} the [[New York Marriott East Side|Shelton Hotel]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=30}} the unbuilt [[Belden Project]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=32}} the [[Master Apartments|Master Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=34}} the [[Waldorf Astoria New York|Waldorf-Astoria Office Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=36}} the lobby of the [[Daily News Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=38}} and the unbuilt [[Convocation Tower]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=40}} Following them are three buildings in [[Detroit]] that Ferriss described as \"undoubtedly the forerunners of the future city\":{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=42}} the [[Penobscot Building|Greater Penobscot Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=42}} the [[Fisher Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=44}} and the [[David Stott Building]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=46}} Following this is a single building in [[Los Angeles]], the [[Los Angeles City Hall|Los Angeles Municipal Tower]], which Ferriss noted was the only true skyscraper in the city at the time due to municipal building height limitations.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=48}}\n\nFerriss concluded the \"Cities of Today\" section by returning to New York City and profiling three recent buildings that were built to unprecedented heights and which were, in Ferriss' opinion, the projects that most foreshadowed future developments in skyscrapers and urban construction more generally.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=50}} To Willis, these were the buildings that \"raised the issues of the race for height and of congestion.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=169}} The three buildings are the [[Chanin Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=50}} the [[Chrysler Building]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=52}} and the [[40 Wall Street|Bank of the Manhattan Company Building]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=54}}\n\n=== \"Projected Trends\" ===\n[[File:Drawing, Study for Maximum Mass Permitted by the 1916 New York Zoning Law, Stage 4, 1922 (CH 18468717).jpg|150px|thumb|Ferriss' drawing on a study for the maximum mass permitted by the [[1916 Zoning Resolution|1916 New York City zoning laws]]]]\n\nThe second section, \"Projected Trends\", begins with a brief vignette about the \"lure of the city\" to young people and prominently discusses practical concerns related to [[population density]] and [[traffic congestion]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=59}} Almost all of the drawings in this section were published or exhibited prior to being included in ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow''.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=170}} In \"Projected Trends\", Ferriss reveals some of his ideas about the power of architecture to influence human thought and behavior, and he proceeds to espouse some of the key elements of [[modern architecture]], especially [[functionalism (architecture)|functionalism]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=60\u201361}} He also voices his objection to densely crowding numerous skyscrapers in close proximity to each other, as well as his opposition to building roads and bridges for automobiles above street level in city centers, both of which were somewhat popular ideas among [[futurist]]s at the time.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=62\u201364}} According to Willis, these drawings depicting densely packed skyscrapers and elevated automobile traffic have ironically \"often been misread as endorsements, whereas Ferriss conceived them as admonitions.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=170}}\n\nFrom here, Ferriss turns his attention to projected trends that he supports: segregating pedestrians from cars by building a system of arcaded walks along buildings, with bridges across intersections one story over street level;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=66}} building skyscraper churches with either apartments or offices accommodating most of the floors, with the [[sanctuary]] either at the base or the top of the building;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=68}} and [[suspension bridge]]s with apartments built into the side of the [[deck (bridge)|bridge deck]] as well as the bridge towers.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=70}} Willis stresses the serious nature of these proposals, observing that \"in the endless invention and boundless expansion of the 1920s, virtually no scheme seemed impossible.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=170}} Ferriss proceeds to describe and diagram the evolution of the setback principle for skyscraper design, in which he likens the architect's work to a [[sculpture|sculptor]] working with [[clay]], and argues that [[1916 Zoning Resolution|New York City's zoning laws]] are actually a blessing in disguise to architects as they all but mandated the adoption of the setback principle.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=72\u201384}}\n\nFerriss continues with a more practical discussion of the advantages of building skyscrapers on wide avenues and spreading them out from other tall buildings,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=86}} as well as the possibility of constructing buildings spanning two blocks or more with streets passing beneath them in scenic tunnels.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=88\u201390}} He then briefly criticizes architects who wish to revert to \"past styles\" with base-shaft-crown construction instead of adhering to his setback principle{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=92}} before then predicting the increasing popularity of [[penthouse apartment]]s,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=94}} [[roof garden|rooftop gardens]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=96}} and the development of \"modern [[ziggurat]]s\" hosting restaurants and theaters, which he viewed as a natural outgrowth of New York City's zoning laws and setback design.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=98}} Ferriss then concludes the section by noting and extolling the virtues of the three most important building materials for future buildings: [[steel]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=104}} [[concrete]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=102}} and (especially) [[architectural glass|glass]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=100}}\n\n=== \"An Imaginary Metropolis\" ===\nThe third section, \"An Imaginary Metropolis\", begins with a theatrical vignette similar to that of the opening section, but this time the curtain rises on \"a city of the imagination\".{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=109}} It features tall buildings, many of them {{Convert|1,000|ft|m}} in height or taller. Instead of being densely packed, however, they are spread apart from each other and are segregated by function. The tall buildings take up three to eight city blocks for their bases, and they are separated from each other by {{Convert|0.5|mi|km}} of low-rise buildings no taller than six stories in height and connected by broad avenues.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=109\u2013111}} Ferriss visualizes this ideal city as having three main zones: a Business Center, the largest of the three centers, and also home to municipal government buildings;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=112}} an Art Center;{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=114}} and a Science Center, which features [[laboratory|laboratories]].{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=116}} He then outlines the sub-centers of the city, also conceptualized functionally: a Finance Center,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=128}} a Technology Center,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=130}} an Industrial Arts Center,{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=132}} and a Philosophy Center.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=136}} These sub-centers are located logically in relation to the centers, so for instance, the Philosophy Center is located between the Art Center and the Science Center.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=171}}\n\nFerriss also sketches plans for a [[fossil fuel power station|coal-fired power plant]],{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=126}} as well as a single skyscraper church shared by all of the city's religious denominations.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=134}} He visualizes the transportation infrastructure of the city as consisting of underground [[rapid transit|subways]] and [[underground parking|car parking]], with ground-level streets for cars.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=130}} Ferriss concludes the section by providing a bird's eye view of this ideal city, which is centered around a triangular Civic Circle with each of the three main zones (Business Center, Art Center, and Science Center) at its corners, with radial avenues fanning out from them to the sub-centers and ultimately on to the outlying districts of the city.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|pp=138\u2013140}} Willis compares this conception to a [[Renaissance]] treatise, noting its \"strong geometric plan which was primarily formal and symbolic, rather than functional\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=171}} Ferriss concludes the book with a brief epilogue that focuses on his belief about how much architecture influences people.{{sfn|Ferriss|1929|p=142}}\n\n== Publication ==\n[[File:HughFerrissAtWork1925.jpg|thumb|Ferriss at work in 1925]]\n\nFerriss received an advance [[royalty payment|royalty]] of $1,000 from the book's publisher, [[Ives Washburn]], in 1929.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}} The book was published in late 1929, after the [[Wall Street Crash of 1929|Wall Street crash]].{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=148}} Of the 60 illustrations featured in the book, only 13 of them were created specifically for ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'', and all of these 13 appear in the final section \"An Imaginary Metropolis\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}}\n\nWriting in 1986, architectural historian Carol Willis noted that the book had been \"long out of print\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=149}} In 1986, [[Princeton Architectural Press]] republished ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' (along with an essay by Willis) as a companion to the exhibition ''Hugh Ferriss: Metropolis'', which was sponsored by the [[Architectural League of New York]] and partially supported by a grant from the [[National Endowment for the Arts]]. The exhibit opened at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art|Whitney Museum]] in New York City and then traveled to the [[Walker Art Center]] in [[Minneapolis]], the [[Art Institute of Chicago]], the [[National Building Museum]] in [[Washington, D.C.]], the Centre de Cr\u00e9ation Industrielle at the [[Centre Georges Pompidou]] in [[Paris]], and the [[Architectural Association School of Architecture|Architectural Association]] in [[London]].{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=iv}}\n\n== Critical reception ==\nContemporary reception to ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' was mostly positive and enthusiastic, and generally regarded Ferriss' ideas for the future city as credible and even practical.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=174}} Albert Guerard of ''Herald Tribune Books'' called the book \"wise and generous in vision, cogent in thought, clear and strong in literary style, appealing as a work of art, magically stirring as a prophecy\".<ref>{{Cite news|title=Tomorrow Seen by Today|last=Guerard|first=Albert|date=January 19, 1930|work=Herald Tribune Books|page=1}}</ref> Joseph G. Niehardt of the ''[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]'' went as far as to declare that he had \"yet to see a book in which the depth of genuine poetic feeling, philosophic grasp and scientific practicality were mysteriously merged.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=On Making Many Books|last=Niehardt|first=John G.|date=December 12, 1929|work=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times Book Review|New York Times Book Review]]'' critic R. L. Duffus expressed some reservations over the scale and density of Ferriss' vision, but nonetheless assumed the inevitability of further centralization and thus his ordering of the future city: \"Monster cities and buildings are already here. They are being built by forces not yet under our control. The task is to subdue them&nbsp;... [and] Mr. Ferriss has contributed something to the fulfillment of that goal.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Metropolis of the Future: Mr. Ferriss Considers the Problem Created by the Skyscraper|last=Duffus|first=R. L.|date=December 8, 1929|work=[[The New York Times Book Review]]|page=10}}</ref>\n\nNegative contemporary reviews of ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' came mostly from proponents of the [[regional planning]] movement.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=175}} In this vein, Geddes Smith wrote that the book \"is certainly beautiful and is probably vicious&nbsp;... because to glorify the American skyscraper is to confirm the thoughtlessness in a perilous fallacy.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=Lovely Monsters|last=Smith|first=Geddes|date=March 15, 1930|work=[[The Survey]]|issue=63|page=727}}</ref> Even more representative of the regional planning movement was the criticism of Regional Plan Association of America member [[Lewis Mumford]],{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=175}} who warned that under Ferriss' proposal \"innumerable human lives will doubtless be sacrificed to Traffic, Commerce, Properly Regulated and Zoned Heights on a scale that will make [[Moloch]] seem an agent of charity.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The Sacred City|last=Mumford|first=Lewis|date=January 27, 1926|work=[[The New Republic]]|issue=45|page=271|author-link=Lewis Mumford}}</ref> Mumford further objected to skyscrapers as \"pyramids of ground rents\",<ref>{{Cite news|title=Skyscrapers in the City of the Future|last=Mumford|first=Lewis|date=April 23, 1930|work=[[The New Republic]]|issue=62|page=275|author-link=Lewis Mumford}}</ref> and warned of the seductive nature of Ferriss' vision to professional [[urban planner]]s as well as the general public, arguing that \"this vulgar dream\" was so powerful that \"even the decent and otherwise enlightened technicians of the New York Committee on the Regional Plan have fallen under it.\"<ref>{{Cite news|title=The City of Tomorrow|last=Mumford|first=Lewis|date=February 12, 1930|work=[[The New Republic]]|issue=61|page=332|author-link=Lewis Mumford}}</ref>\n\nWriting in 1986, Carol Willis notes that Ferriss' \"future city seems decidedly a fantasy, exaggerated in its scale and hierarchical order, and certainly impracticable.\"{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=174}} She further writes that with the benefit of \"today's historical distance, the impressive scale and harmonious ensembles of Ferriss' colossal towers and the formal hierarchy of his ideal city seem obviously impracticable and politically naive\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=148}} Furthermore, she observes that Ferriss' \"ideal metropolis radically contradicts most current opinion on the best qualities of a liveable city\", most notably \"an emphasis on pedestrian scale, public spaces, historic preservation and a heterogeneous urban fabric\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=148}} More concretely, Willis notes that while Ferriss detailed some features of the city in great detail, \"many other aspects of urban life were completely ignored\",{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}} including schools, hospitals, police stations, post offices, stadiums, movie theaters, factories, and residences.{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=173}} She observes that while the first two sections of the book \"linked current conditions and future projects\", the third and final section \"presented not an extrapolation or evolution of the contemporary city, but a utopia created ''[[ex novo]]''\".{{sfn|Willis|1986|p=174}}\n\n[[File:Justin Davidson introduces his book Magnetic City at Columbia GSAPP (cropped).jpg|125px|thumb|[[Justin Davidson]]]]\n\nIn 2016, while writing for ''[[CityLab]]'', [[Carl Abbott (urban historian)|Carl Abbott]] described the \"unrestrained imagination\" of Ferriss that \"created a city of the future in which step-pyramid towers rise from vaguely glimpsed streets\".<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.citylab.com/life/2016/10/behind-the-urbanism-in-science-fiction/504716/|title=Behind the Urbanism in Science Fiction|last=Abbott|first=Carl|date=October 21, 2016|work=[[CityLab]]|access-date=May 27, 2019|author-link=Carl Abbott (urban historian)}}</ref> In his observation, Ferriss drew \"fantastic views\" filled with \"hypertrophied Chrysler Buildings and superscaled [[Rockefeller Center]]s\".<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2017, Ramona Albert, founder and [[principal (architecture)|principal]] of Ramona Albert Architecture, wrote that in ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'', Ferriss \"offers an eerily accurate depiction of what cities could look like in the future, even though it was written almost a century ago.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.greenbiz.com/article/3-big-ways-sustainable-design-will-shape-future-cities|title=3 big ways sustainable design will shape future cities|last=Albert|first=Ramona|date=May 10, 2017|work=[[GreenBiz]]|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> According to [[Justin Davidson]], writing in 2017 for ''[[New York (magazine)|New York]]'' magazine, Ferriss \"understood the romance embedded in the new zoning code\" and, in his writing, was able to transform the zoning code into a \"spectacularly utopian tool\".<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://nymag.com/intelligencer/2017/04/nyc-walking-tour-of-42nd-street.html|title=A Walking Tour of 42nd Street|last=Davidson|first=Justin|date=April 2017|work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]]|access-date=May 27, 2019|author-link=Justin Davidson}}</ref> Furthermore, he argued that ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow \"''shaped the dreams of architects, planners, comic-book illustrators, and Hollywood set designers.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWriting for ''[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]'' in 2018, Darren Garrett argued that the third section of ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' echoed [[Ebenezer Howard]]'s ''[[Garden Cities of To-morrow]]'' while also illustrating Ferriss' \"plans for an entire city that showcases not only his draughtsmanship, but his forward-looking ideas on urban planning\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://qz.com/quartzy/1342049/weird-and-wonderful-visions-of-the-future-that-never-came-to-pass/|title=Weird and wonderful visions of the future that never came to pass|last=Garrett|first=Darren|date=August 5, 2018|work=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]]|access-date=May 27, 2019}}</ref> He further observed that Ferriss' drawings went beyond simple [[architectural rendering]]s, as \"his dramatic sense of light and shadow depict cities strangely devoid of people, or solo figures dwarfed by their majestic surroundings.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Also in 2018, [[Andrew Berman]] of the [[Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation]] wrote that ''The Metropolis of Tomorrow'' \"influenced a generation of architects who created some of the most striking and memorable buildings of the era, including the [[Empire State Building|Empire State]] and Chrysler Buildings.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.6sqft.com/from-mark-twain-and-the-lovin-spoonful-to-tech-hub-exploring-the-overlooked-history-of-union-square-south/|title=From Mark Twain and the Lovin' Spoonful to Tech Hub: The overlooked history of Union Square South|last=Berman|first=Andrew|date=December 7, 2018|work=6sqft|access-date=May 27, 2019|author-link=Andrew Berman}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== Sources ==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last = Ferriss |first = Hugh |author-link = Hugh Ferriss |title = The Metropolis of Tomorrow |url = https://archive.org/details/mettomo00ferr |date = 1929 |publisher = [[Ives Washburn]] }}\n*{{cite book |ref = harv |last = Willis |first = Carol |author-link = Carol Willis (architectural historian) |chapter = Drawing Towards Metropolis |title = The Metropolis of Tomorrow |date = 1986 |publisher = [[Princeton Architectural Press]] |isbn = 0-910413-11-8 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Metropolis of Tomorrow, The}}\n\n[[Category:1929 books]]\n[[Category:Books about urbanism]]\n[[Category:Design books]]\n[[Category:Futurology books]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1929 bookstoCategory:1929 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Metropolis_of_Tomorrow"}
{"title_page": "The New Despotism", "text_new": "{{Infobox book \n| name = The New Despotism\n| orig title =\n| translator = \n| image = \n| author = [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Lord Hewart of Bury]]\n| cover_artist = \n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| series = \n| subject = Law and Politics\n| genre = \n| publisher = Ernest Benn Limited\n| release_date = 1929\n| media_type =\n| pages = vii+308\n| size_weight =\n| isbn = \n| preceded_by = \n| followed_by = \n}}\n'''''The New Despotism''''' is a book written by the [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Lord Hewart]], [[Lord Chief Justice of England]], and published in 1929 by [[Ernest Benn Limited]]. Hewart described this \"new despotism\" as \"to subordinate Parliament, to evade the Courts, and to render the will, or the caprice, of the Executive unfettered and supreme\".<ref>Lord Hewart, ''The New Despotism'' (London: Ernest Benn Limited, 1929), p. 17.</ref>  The evasion of the Courts referred to increasing quasi-judicial decision-making by the civil service and the subordination of Parliament which resulted from the growth of delegated legislation.\n\n==Contents==\nI. The Nature of the Question<br />II. The Rule of Law<br />III. \"Administrative Law\"<br />IV. Administrative Lawlessness<br />V. The System at Work<br />VI. Departmental Legislation<br />VII. The Independence of the Judiciary<br />VIII. What is to be done?<br />IX. Some leading cases<br />X. Examples from statutes\n\n==Reaction==\n\nThe book created \"a constitutional and political storm\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/MqLJ/2004/2.html|year=2004|title=REGULATIONS REVIEW IN THE NEW ZEALAND PARLIAMENT|journal=[[Macquarie Law Journal]]|volume=4|issue=7}}</ref> It was rumoured that Whitehall \"considered an attempt to boycott it\".<ref>John Ramsden (ed.), ''Oxford Companion to Twentieth Century British Politics'' (Oxford University Press, 2005), p. 299.</ref> In response the British Government appointed the Donoughmore Committee (chaired by [[Richard Hely-Hutchinson, 6th Earl of Donoughmore|Lord Donoughmore]]) to review the powers of Ministers, however its Report (1932; Cmd. 4060) did not share Hewart's alarm.\n\nThe book and the Donoughmore Report provoked a group of socialist lawyers and political scientists, notably Professor [[Harold Laski]] (a member of the Donoughmore Committee) and Sir (William) [[Ivor Jennings]] to criticise the [[A. V. Dicey|Diceyan]] concept of the rule of law.<ref>W. I. Jennings, 'Administrative Law and Administrative Jurisdiction', ''Journal of Comparative Legislation and International Law'', 3rd series, XX (1938), p. 103. W. I. Jennings, 'The Report on Ministers' Powers', ''Public Administration'', Vols. X (1932) and XI (1933). W. I. Jennings, ''The Law and the Constitution'' (London: 1933).</ref>\n\nIn 1956, [[Richard Crossman]] published a [[Fabian Society]] tract titled ''Socialism and the New Despotism'' where he hoped reform of the judiciary would make the judiciary \"regain the traditional function of defending individual rights against encroachment\".<ref>R. H. S. Crossman, ''Socialism and the New Despotism'' (London: Fabian Tracts, No. 298, 1956), p. 12.</ref>\n\nThe book was a favourite of [[Margaret Thatcher|Margaret Thatcher's]].<ref>Keith Sutherland, ''The Party's Over'' (Imprint Academic, 2004), p. 63, n. 3.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Despotism}}\n[[Category:1929 non-fiction books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book \n| name = The New Despotism\n| orig title =\n| translator = \n| image = \n| author = [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Lord Hewart of Bury]]\n| cover_artist = \n| country = United Kingdom\n| language = English\n| series = \n| subject = Law and Politics\n| genre = \n| publisher = Ernest Benn Limited\n| release_date = 1929\n| media_type =\n| pages = vii+308\n| size_weight =\n| isbn = \n| preceded_by = \n| followed_by = \n}}\n'''''The New Despotism''''' is a book written by the [[Gordon Hewart, 1st Viscount Hewart|Lord Hewart]], [[Lord Chief Justice of England]], and published in 1929 by [[Ernest Benn Limited]]. Hewart described this \"new despotism\" as \"to subordinate Parliament, to evade the Courts, and to render the will, or the caprice, of the Executive unfettered and supreme\".<ref>Lord Hewart, ''The New Despotism'' (London: Ernest Benn Limited, 1929), p. 17.</ref>  The evasion of the Courts referred to increasing quasi-judicial decision-making by the civil service and the subordination of Parliament which resulted from the growth of delegated legislation.\n\n==Contents==\nI. The Nature of the Question<br />II. The Rule of Law<br />III. \"Administrative Law\"<br />IV. Administrative Lawlessness<br />V. The System at Work<br />VI. Departmental Legislation<br />VII. The Independence of the Judiciary<br />VIII. What is to be done?<br />IX. Some leading cases<br />X. Examples from statutes\n\n==Reaction==\n\nThe book created \"a constitutional and political storm\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.austlii.edu.au/au/journals/MqLJ/2004/2.html|year=2004|title=REGULATIONS REVIEW IN THE NEW ZEALAND PARLIAMENT|journal=[[Macquarie Law Journal]]|volume=4|issue=7}}</ref> It was rumoured that Whitehall \"considered an attempt to boycott it\".<ref>John Ramsden (ed.), ''Oxford Companion to Twentieth Century British Politics'' (Oxford University Press, 2005), p. 299.</ref> In response the British Government appointed the Donoughmore Committee (chaired by [[Richard Hely-Hutchinson, 6th Earl of Donoughmore|Lord Donoughmore]]) to review the powers of Ministers, however its Report (1932; Cmd. 4060) did not share Hewart's alarm.\n\nThe book and the Donoughmore Report provoked a group of socialist lawyers and political scientists, notably Professor [[Harold Laski]] (a member of the Donoughmore Committee) and Sir (William) [[Ivor Jennings]] to criticise the [[A. V. Dicey|Diceyan]] concept of the rule of law.<ref>W. I. Jennings, 'Administrative Law and Administrative Jurisdiction', ''Journal of Comparative Legislation and International Law'', 3rd series, XX (1938), p. 103. W. I. Jennings, 'The Report on Ministers' Powers', ''Public Administration'', Vols. X (1932) and XI (1933). W. I. Jennings, ''The Law and the Constitution'' (London: 1933).</ref>\n\nIn 1956, [[Richard Crossman]] published a [[Fabian Society]] tract titled ''Socialism and the New Despotism'' where he hoped reform of the judiciary would make the judiciary \"regain the traditional function of defending individual rights against encroachment\".<ref>R. H. S. Crossman, ''Socialism and the New Despotism'' (London: Fabian Tracts, No. 298, 1956), p. 12.</ref>\n\nThe book was a favourite of [[Margaret Thatcher|Margaret Thatcher's]].<ref>Keith Sutherland, ''The Party's Over'' (Imprint Academic, 2004), p. 63, n. 3.</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:New Despotism}}\n[[Category:1929 books]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1929 bookstoCategory:1929 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_Despotism"}
{"title_page": "Now and After", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n|name = Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism\n|title_orig = |translator =\n|image = Now and After cover.jpg\n|caption = Title page of the first edition.\n|author = [[Alexander Berkman]]\n|illustrator = |cover_artist = |country = |language = |series =\n|subject = {{unbulleted list |[[Anarchism]] |[[Anarchist communism]]}}\n|genre = [[Political philosophy]]\n|published = 1929 ([[Vanguard Press]])\n|media_type = Print\n|pages =\n|isbn =\n|oclc = 83572649\n|preceded_by = [[The Bolshevik Myth]]\n|followed_by =\n}}\n{{Anarcho-communism sidebar |Works}}\n\n'''''Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism''''' is an introduction to the principles of [[anarchism]] and [[anarchist communism]] written by [[Alexander Berkman]]. First published in 1929 by Vanguard Press, after parts of it had appeared in the ''[[Freie Arbeiter Stimme]]'', ''Now and After'' has been reprinted many times, often under the title '''''What Is Communist Anarchism?''''' or '''''What Is Anarchism?'''''.<ref name=Pateman>Berkman, p. viii (Introduction by Barry Pateman).</ref> Because of its presentation of anarchist philosophy in plain language, ''Now and After'' has become one of the best-known introductions to anarchism in print. Anarchist [[Stuart Christie]] wrote that ''Now and After'' is \"among the best introductions to the ideas of anarchism in the English language\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Building a Library: Anarchy |last=Christie |first=Stuart |authorlink=Stuart Christie |date=July 24, 2005 |work=[[The Independent]] }}</ref> Historian [[Paul Avrich]] described it as \"a classic\" and wrote that it was \"the clearest exposition of communist anarchism in English or any other language\".<ref name=Avrich>Avrich, p. 206.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe anarchist movement was under siege during the 1920s. The United States had deported hundreds of anarchists, including Berkman and [[Emma Goldman]], in 1919. In the newly created [[Soviet Union]], [[Anarchism in Russia|Russian anarchists]] were being arrested by the [[Cheka]] and imprisoned or executed.<ref>Raleigh, p. 169.</ref> In [[Free Territory|Ukraine]], an [[Revolutionary Insurrectionary Army of Ukraine|anarchist army]] led by [[Nestor Makhno]] had been defeated by the [[Red Army]].<ref>Kenez, p. 45.</ref> Hundreds of Russian anarchists were fleeing to exile in Germany and France.\n\nIn an effort to revive the movement, the [[Jewish Anarchist Federation]] in [[New York City|New York]] asked Berkman in 1926 to write an introduction to anarchism intended for the general public.<ref name=Avrich/> By presenting the principles of anarchism in plain language, the New York anarchists hoped that readers might be swayed to support the movement or, at a minimum, that the book might improve the image of anarchism and anarchists in the public's eyes.\n\n== The book ==\n\nBerkman's work explains anarchist philosophy in terms that uninitiated readers can understand. The book's chapters are brief, and many of them begin with questions (''e.g.'', \"Is Anarchism Violence?\", \"Will Communist Anarchism Work?\"). A number of the ideas he discusses are similar to those proposed in ''[[The Conquest of Bread]]'' by [[Peter Kropotkin]], whom Berkman cites throughout. Berkman avoids the sort of jargon and technical language that is often used by political writers in favor of plain language. As he writes in his foreword:\n\n{{quote|Anarchist books, with few exceptions, are not accessible to the understanding of the average reader. It is the common failing of most works dealing with social questions that they are written on the assumption that the reader is already familiar to a considerable extent with the subject, which is generally not the case at all. As a result there are very few books treating of social problems in a sufficiently simple and intelligible manner.\n\nFor the above reason I consider a restatement of the Anarchist position very much needed at this time\u2014a restatement in the plainest and clearest terms which can be understood by every one. That is, an ABC of Anarchism.<ref>Berkman, p. xiii.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1929, ''Now and After'' was published by Vanguard Press in New York. In 1937, a year after Berkman's death, a second edition was published with a preface by Emma Goldman. A British edition was published in 1942 by [[Freedom Press]] in [[London]]. Since then, the book has been reprinted many times.<ref name=Pateman/>\n\n== References ==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n*[[Paul Avrich|Avrich, Paul]]. ''Anarchist Portraits''. Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1988. {{ISBN|0-691-00609-1}}.\n*Berkman, Alexander. ''What is Anarchism?'' Oakland: AK Press, 2003. {{ISBN|1-902593-70-7}}.\n*Kenez, Peter. ''A History of the Soviet Union from the Beginning to the End''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2006. {{ISBN|0-521-86437-2}}.\n*Raleigh, Donald J. ''Experiencing Russia's Civil War: Politics, Society, and Revolutionary Culture in Saratov, 1917-1922''. Princeton: Princeton University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-691-11320-3}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism|Now and After}}\n'''Online editions of ''Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism'':'''\n*[http://dwardmac.pitzer.edu/Anarchist_Archives/bright/berkman/comanarchism/whatis_toc.html HTML] at [[Anarchy Archives]]\n*[http://dwardmac.pitzer.edu/Anarchist_Archives/bright/berkman/communistanarchy.pdf PDF] at [[Anarchy Archives]]\n*[http://www.anarchyisorder.org/CD%234/Lay-outed%20texts/PDF-versions/Berkman,%20Alexander%20-%20Now%20and%20after%20(ABC%20of%20communist%20anarchi.pdf PDF] at Anarchy is Order\n*[http://libcom.org/library/what-is-anarchism-alexander-berkman HTML] at Libcom\n*[http://theanarchistlibrary.org/library/alexander-berkman-what-is-communist-anarchism Multiple formats, including ePub] at the Anarchist Library\n\n<!--Footers-->\n{{Anarchism}}\n\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:1929 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about anarchism]]\n[[Category:Philosophy books]]\n[[Category:Vanguard Press books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n|name = Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism\n|title_orig = |translator =\n|image = Now and After cover.jpg\n|caption = Title page of the first edition.\n|author = [[Alexander Berkman]]\n|illustrator = |cover_artist = |country = |language = |series =\n|subject = {{unbulleted list |[[Anarchism]] |[[Anarchist communism]]}}\n|genre = [[Political philosophy]]\n|published = 1929 ([[Vanguard Press]])\n|media_type = Print\n|pages =\n|isbn =\n|oclc = 83572649\n|preceded_by = [[The Bolshevik Myth]]\n|followed_by =\n}}\n{{Anarcho-communism sidebar |Works}}\n\n'''''Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism''''' is an introduction to the principles of [[anarchism]] and [[anarchist communism]] written by [[Alexander Berkman]]. First published in 1929 by Vanguard Press, after parts of it had appeared in the ''[[Freie Arbeiter Stimme]]'', ''Now and After'' has been reprinted many times, often under the title '''''What Is Communist Anarchism?''''' or '''''What Is Anarchism?'''''.<ref name=Pateman>Berkman, p. viii (Introduction by Barry Pateman).</ref> Because of its presentation of anarchist philosophy in plain language, ''Now and After'' has become one of the best-known introductions to anarchism in print. Anarchist [[Stuart Christie]] wrote that ''Now and After'' is \"among the best introductions to the ideas of anarchism in the English language\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Building a Library: Anarchy |last=Christie |first=Stuart |authorlink=Stuart Christie |date=July 24, 2005 |work=[[The Independent]] }}</ref> Historian [[Paul Avrich]] described it as \"a classic\" and wrote that it was \"the clearest exposition of communist anarchism in English or any other language\".<ref name=Avrich>Avrich, p. 206.</ref>\n\n== History ==\n\nThe anarchist movement was under siege during the 1920s. The United States had deported hundreds of anarchists, including Berkman and [[Emma Goldman]], in 1919. In the newly created [[Soviet Union]], [[Anarchism in Russia|Russian anarchists]] were being arrested by the [[Cheka]] and imprisoned or executed.<ref>Raleigh, p. 169.</ref> In [[Free Territory|Ukraine]], an [[Revolutionary Insurrectionary Army of Ukraine|anarchist army]] led by [[Nestor Makhno]] had been defeated by the [[Red Army]].<ref>Kenez, p. 45.</ref> Hundreds of Russian anarchists were fleeing to exile in Germany and France.\n\nIn an effort to revive the movement, the [[Jewish Anarchist Federation]] in [[New York City|New York]] asked Berkman in 1926 to write an introduction to anarchism intended for the general public.<ref name=Avrich/> By presenting the principles of anarchism in plain language, the New York anarchists hoped that readers might be swayed to support the movement or, at a minimum, that the book might improve the image of anarchism and anarchists in the public's eyes.\n\n== The book ==\n\nBerkman's work explains anarchist philosophy in terms that uninitiated readers can understand. The book's chapters are brief, and many of them begin with questions (''e.g.'', \"Is Anarchism Violence?\", \"Will Communist Anarchism Work?\"). A number of the ideas he discusses are similar to those proposed in ''[[The Conquest of Bread]]'' by [[Peter Kropotkin]], whom Berkman cites throughout. Berkman avoids the sort of jargon and technical language that is often used by political writers in favor of plain language. As he writes in his foreword:\n\n{{quote|Anarchist books, with few exceptions, are not accessible to the understanding of the average reader. It is the common failing of most works dealing with social questions that they are written on the assumption that the reader is already familiar to a considerable extent with the subject, which is generally not the case at all. As a result there are very few books treating of social problems in a sufficiently simple and intelligible manner.\n\nFor the above reason I consider a restatement of the Anarchist position very much needed at this time\u2014a restatement in the plainest and clearest terms which can be understood by every one. That is, an ABC of Anarchism.<ref>Berkman, p. xiii.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1929, ''Now and After'' was published by Vanguard Press in New York. In 1937, a year after Berkman's death, a second edition was published with a preface by Emma Goldman. A British edition was published in 1942 by [[Freedom Press]] in [[London]]. Since then, the book has been reprinted many times.<ref name=Pateman/>\n\n== References ==\n\n===Footnotes===\n{{reflist}}\n\n===Works cited===\n*[[Paul Avrich|Avrich, Paul]]. ''Anarchist Portraits''. Princeton: Princeton University Press, 1988. {{ISBN|0-691-00609-1}}.\n*Berkman, Alexander. ''What is Anarchism?'' Oakland: AK Press, 2003. {{ISBN|1-902593-70-7}}.\n*Kenez, Peter. ''A History of the Soviet Union from the Beginning to the End''. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press, 2006. {{ISBN|0-521-86437-2}}.\n*Raleigh, Donald J. ''Experiencing Russia's Civil War: Politics, Society, and Revolutionary Culture in Saratov, 1917-1922''. Princeton: Princeton University Press, 2002. {{ISBN|0-691-11320-3}}.\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikisource|Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism|Now and After}}\n'''Online editions of ''Now and After: The ABC of Communist Anarchism'':'''\n*[http://dwardmac.pitzer.edu/Anarchist_Archives/bright/berkman/comanarchism/whatis_toc.html HTML] at [[Anarchy Archives]]\n*[http://dwardmac.pitzer.edu/Anarchist_Archives/bright/berkman/communistanarchy.pdf PDF] at [[Anarchy Archives]]\n*[http://www.anarchyisorder.org/CD%234/Lay-outed%20texts/PDF-versions/Berkman,%20Alexander%20-%20Now%20and%20after%20(ABC%20of%20communist%20anarchi.pdf PDF] at Anarchy is Order\n*[http://libcom.org/library/what-is-anarchism-alexander-berkman HTML] at Libcom\n*[http://theanarchistlibrary.org/library/alexander-berkman-what-is-communist-anarchism Multiple formats, including ePub] at the Anarchist Library\n\n<!--Footers-->\n{{Anarchism}}\n\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:1929 books]]\n[[Category:Books about anarchism]]\n[[Category:Philosophy books]]\n[[Category:Vanguard Press books]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1929 bookstoCategory:1929 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Now_and_After"}
{"title_page": "Marriage and Morals", "text_new": "[[File:MarriageAndMorals.jpg|thumb|First edition (publ. [[Allen & Unwin]])]]\n\n'''''Marriage and Morals''''' is a 1929 book by philosopher [[Bertrand Russell]], in which the author questions the [[Victorian morality|Victorian notions of morality]] regarding sex and marriage.\n\nRussell argues that the laws and ideas about sex of his time were a potpourri from various sources and were no longer valid. The subjects range from criticisms of social norms, theories about their origins and tendencies, evolutionary psychology, and instinctual attachment to children (or lack thereof), among others. Notably, the book found [[marital rape]] to be common, stating: \"Marriage is for woman the commonest mode of livelihood, and the total amount of undesired sex endured by women is probably greater in marriage than in [[prostitution]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notable-quotes.com/r/russell_bertrand.html |title=Bertrand Russell Quotes |publisher=Notable-quotes.com |accessdate=2013-06-15}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural response==\n''Marriage and Morals'' prompted vigorous protests against and denunciations of Russell during his visit to the United States shortly after the book's publication.<ref name=SexEdPioneers>{{cite web|title=Pioneers of Sex Education |url=http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/ATLAS_EN/html/pioneers_of_sex_education.html |author=Haeberle, Erwin J. |year=1983 |accessdate=2008-02-17 |publisher=The Continuum Publishing Company |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313020717/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/ATLAS_EN/html/pioneers_of_sex_education.html |archivedate=2008-03-13 }}</ref> A decade later, the book, along with his protest of US involvement in WWI and his generally controversial position in public discourse, cost him his professorial appointment at the [[City College of New York]] due to a court judgment from a Catholic judge that his opinions made him \"morally unfit\" to teach. A public outcry, initiated by the mother of a student who was ineligible for his course in [[mathematical logic]], preceded the ruling. [[John Dewey]] and several other intellectuals protested his treatment.<ref name=Denied>{{cite web|title=Appointment Denied: The Inquisition of Bertrand Russell|author=Leberstein, Stephen|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3860/is_200111/ai_n9008065|publisher=Academe|date=November\u2013December 2001|accessdate=2008-02-17}}</ref> [[Albert Einstein]]'s often-quoted aphorism that \"Great spirits have always encountered violent opposition from mediocre minds\" is from his open letter in support of Russell.<ref>[http://www.asl-associates.com/einsteinquotes.htm Einstein quotations and sources.] Retrieved July 9, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Eugenics==\nIn chapter eighteen, Russell expresses his support for [[eugenics]].\n\n==Nobel Prize==\n\nAccording to Russell, he was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] for ''Marriage and Morals''.<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Russell\n| first = Bertrand\n| title = Autobiography\n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=SlMrmmrNuEoC&pg=PA521&dq=bertrand+russell+autobiography+christina#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| page = 521\n| accessdate = 4 June 2013\n| isbn = 9780415189859\n| year = 1998\n}}</ref>\n{{Quote\n| text = When I was called to Stockholm, at the end of 1950, to receive the Nobel Prize &ndash; somewhat to my surprise, for literature, for my book ''Marriage and Morals'' &ndash; I was apprehensive, since I remembered that, exactly 300&nbsp;years earlier, Descartes had been called to Scandinavia by [[Christina, Queen of Sweden|Queen Christina]] in the winter time and had died of the cold.\n}}\n\nThe Nobel Foundation, on the other hand, wrote that the prize recognized \"his varied and significant writings in which he champions humanitarian ideals and freedom of thought\"; not any particular work.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikiquote-inline}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/marriagemorals00russ_0/ Full text at archive.org]\n\n{{Italic title}}\n\n[[Category:1929 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about the philosophy of sexuality]]\n[[Category:Books by Bertrand Russell]]\n[[Category:Marriage]]\n[[Category:Ethics books]]\n[[Category:Allen & Unwin books]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:MarriageAndMorals.jpg|thumb|First edition (publ. [[Allen & Unwin]])]]\n\n'''''Marriage and Morals''''' is a 1929 book by philosopher [[Bertrand Russell]], in which the author questions the [[Victorian morality|Victorian notions of morality]] regarding sex and marriage.\n\nRussell argues that the laws and ideas about sex of his time were a potpourri from various sources and were no longer valid. The subjects range from criticisms of social norms, theories about their origins and tendencies, evolutionary psychology, and instinctual attachment to children (or lack thereof), among others. Notably, the book found [[marital rape]] to be common, stating: \"Marriage is for woman the commonest mode of livelihood, and the total amount of undesired sex endured by women is probably greater in marriage than in [[prostitution]].\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notable-quotes.com/r/russell_bertrand.html |title=Bertrand Russell Quotes |publisher=Notable-quotes.com |accessdate=2013-06-15}}</ref>\n\n==Cultural response==\n''Marriage and Morals'' prompted vigorous protests against and denunciations of Russell during his visit to the United States shortly after the book's publication.<ref name=SexEdPioneers>{{cite web|title=Pioneers of Sex Education |url=http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/ATLAS_EN/html/pioneers_of_sex_education.html |author=Haeberle, Erwin J. |year=1983 |accessdate=2008-02-17 |publisher=The Continuum Publishing Company |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080313020717/http://www2.hu-berlin.de/sexology/ATLAS_EN/html/pioneers_of_sex_education.html |archivedate=2008-03-13 }}</ref> A decade later, the book, along with his protest of US involvement in WWI and his generally controversial position in public discourse, cost him his professorial appointment at the [[City College of New York]] due to a court judgment from a Catholic judge that his opinions made him \"morally unfit\" to teach. A public outcry, initiated by the mother of a student who was ineligible for his course in [[mathematical logic]], preceded the ruling. [[John Dewey]] and several other intellectuals protested his treatment.<ref name=Denied>{{cite web|title=Appointment Denied: The Inquisition of Bertrand Russell|author=Leberstein, Stephen|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qa3860/is_200111/ai_n9008065|publisher=Academe|date=November\u2013December 2001|accessdate=2008-02-17}}</ref> [[Albert Einstein]]'s often-quoted aphorism that \"Great spirits have always encountered violent opposition from mediocre minds\" is from his open letter in support of Russell.<ref>[http://www.asl-associates.com/einsteinquotes.htm Einstein quotations and sources.] Retrieved July 9, 2009.</ref>\n\n==Eugenics==\nIn chapter eighteen, Russell expresses his support for [[eugenics]].\n\n==Nobel Prize==\n\nAccording to Russell, he was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] for ''Marriage and Morals''.<ref>{{cite book\n| last = Russell\n| first = Bertrand\n| title = Autobiography\n| url = https://books.google.com/?id=SlMrmmrNuEoC&pg=PA521&dq=bertrand+russell+autobiography+christina#v=onepage&q&f=false\n| page = 521\n| accessdate = 4 June 2013\n| isbn = 9780415189859\n| year = 1998\n}}</ref>\n{{Quote\n| text = When I was called to Stockholm, at the end of 1950, to receive the Nobel Prize &ndash; somewhat to my surprise, for literature, for my book ''Marriage and Morals'' &ndash; I was apprehensive, since I remembered that, exactly 300&nbsp;years earlier, Descartes had been called to Scandinavia by [[Christina, Queen of Sweden|Queen Christina]] in the winter time and had died of the cold.\n}}\n\nThe Nobel Foundation, on the other hand, wrote that the prize recognized \"his varied and significant writings in which he champions humanitarian ideals and freedom of thought\"; not any particular work.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikiquote-inline}}\n*[https://archive.org/details/marriagemorals00russ_0/ Full text at archive.org]\n\n{{Italic title}}\n\n[[Category:1929 books]]\n[[Category:Books about the philosophy of sexuality]]\n[[Category:Books by Bertrand Russell]]\n[[Category:Marriage]]\n[[Category:Ethics books]]\n[[Category:Allen & Unwin books]]\n", "name_user": "I grieve in stereo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Moving fromCategory:1929 bookstoCategory:1929 non-fiction booksusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marriage_and_Morals"}
{"title_page": "Christus (statue)", "text_new": "{{for|the statue of Jesus in Indianapolis, Indiana|Christus (Indianapolis)}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[File:Thorvaldsen Christus.jpg|thumb|200px|The original statue at the [[Church of Our Lady (Copenhagen)|Church of Our Lady]], [[Copenhagen]].]]\n'''''Christus''''' (also known as '''''Christus Consolator''''') is a 19th-century [[Carrara marble]] statue of the [[resurrection of Jesus|resurrected]] [[Jesus]] by [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]. Since its completion in 1838, the statue has been located in the [[Church of Denmark|Evangelical Lutheran Church in Denmark]]'s [[Church of Our Lady (Copenhagen)|Church of Our Lady]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. In the 20th century, images and replicas of the statue were adopted by the leaders of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) to emphasize the centrality of Jesus Christ in church teachings.\n\n==Original sculpture==\nThorvaldsen was commissioned to sculpt statues of Jesus and the apostles for the [[Church of Our Lady (Copenhagen)|Church of Our Lady]] in Copenhagen. The statue of Jesus was completed in 1821.The statue is 345 centimeter high.<ref>{{cite book |title=Billeder og billedkunst |last=Villadsen |first=Ole |authorlink= |coauthors= |year= |publisher=Gyldendal |location= |isbn= 87-00-33896-6|page=102|pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> The inscription at the base of the sculpture reads \"Kommer til mig\" (\"Come to me\") with a reference to the Bible verse: [[Matthew 11:28]].\n\nThe ''Christus'' was not well known outside of Denmark until 1896, when an American textbook writer wrote that the statue was \"considered the most perfect statue of Christ in the world.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Coe |first= Fanny E. |editor-last= Dunton |editor-first= Larkin |title= Modern Europe |url= https://archive.org/details/worldanditspeop01duntgoog |place= Boston |publisher= [[Silver Burdett]] |series= The Young Folks' Library '''9''', The World and Its People '''5''' |year= 1896 |page = [https://archive.org/stream/worldanditspeop01duntgoog#page/n132/mode/1up 126] |oclc= 14865981 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|reason=Cited work is a primary document and cannot justify the claim.|date=December 2019}}{{dubious|Not known outside Denmark?||date=December 2019}}\n\n==Use by The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints==\nIn the 1950s, [[Stephen L Richards]], a church [[Apostle (LDS Church)|apostle]], purchased a 3.4-metre (11-foot) replica of the ''Christus'' and presented it to [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|church president]] [[David O. McKay]]. In 1966, the statue was placed at the church's [[Temple Square]] in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]]. The church's second ''Christus'' replica was created to be displayed in its pavilion at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]]. The display of the replica \"was intended to help visitors understand that Latter-day Saints are Christians\".<ref name = EOM>{{citation |authorlink= Florence S. Jacobsen |first= Florence S. |last= Jacobsen |contribution= Christus Statue |contribution-url= http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/EoM/id/5596 |pages= 273\u2013274 |editor1-last= Ludlow |editor1-first= Daniel H |editor1-link= Daniel H. Ludlow |title= [[Encyclopedia of Mormonism]] |location= New York |publisher= [[Macmillan Publishing]] |year= 1992 |isbn= 0-02-879602-0 |oclc= 24502140}}</ref>\n\nSince the display of the ''Christus'' at the World's Fair and at Temple Square, the church has created replicas of the statue and displayed them in visitors' centers near [[Temple (LDS Church)|LDS temples]] in [[Hamilton New Zealand Temple|Hamilton, New Zealand]]; [[Laie Hawaii Temple|Laie, Hawaii]]; [[Los Angeles California Temple|Los Angeles, California]]; [[Mesa Arizona Temple|Mesa, Arizona]]; [[Mexico City Mexico Temple|Mexico City]]; [[Nauvoo Illinois Temple|Nauvoo, Illinois]]; [[Oakland California Temple|Oakland, California]]; [[Palmyra New York Temple|Palmyra, New York]]; [[London England Temple|London, England]]; [[Portland Oregon Temple|Portland, Oregon]]; [[Rome Italy Temple|Rome, Italy]]; [[St. George Utah Temple|St. George, Utah]]; [[Washington D.C. Temple|Washington, D.C.]]; [[Paris France Temple|Paris, France]]; [[S\u00e3o Paulo Brazil Temple|S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil]]; and [[Provo City Center Temple|Provo, Utah]].<ref name = EOM/><ref name = Richardson>{{citation |authorlink= Matthew O. Richardson |first= Matthew O. |last= Richardson |url= http://ldsliving.com/story/4910-the-ichristusi-legacy |title= The ''Christus'' Legacy |journal= [[Deseret Book|LDS Living Magazine]] |date= February 29, 2008 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140513011608/http://ldsliving.com/story/4910-the-ichristusi-legacy |archivedate= 2014-05-13 |url-status= live }}. Excerpted from: {{citation |last= Richardson |first= Matthew O.  |title= The Christus Legacy |place= Sandy, Utah |publisher= Leatherwood Press |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-1599920405 |oclc= 157000118 }}</ref> Replicas are also on display at the church's visitors' centers at the [[Hill Cumorah]] and in [[Independence, Missouri]].<ref name = Richardson/> The church uses the image of the ''Christus'' on its webpages and in other official publications<ref name = Richardson/>\n\nOn April 4, 2020, [[Russell M. Nelson]] announced a new symbol to be used, which has an image of the Christus as a central element along with the church's name.<ref>{{citation |url= https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/new-symbol-church-of-jesus-christ |title= [[The Church\u2019s New Symbol Emphasizes the Centrality of the Savior]]}}</ref>\n\n==Other replicas==\nA full-size replica of the ''Christus'' is located in [[The Johns Hopkins Hospital]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]; the hospital refers to the statue as ''Christus Consolator''.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/dome/0312/feature.cfm |title= A Provocative Icon |journal= Dome |volume= 54 |issue= 10 |page= 1 |first= Lindsay |last= Roylance |date= December 2003 |publisher= [[Johns Hopkins Medicine]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051048/http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/dome/0312/feature.cfm |archivedate= 2013-12-03 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nA replica is located at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]] in Glendale, California in \"The Court of the Christus\" on Cathedral Drive.<ref>http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~263065~5524046:Pictorial-Map-and-Visitor-s-Guide-t</ref>\n\nIn 2009, a six-foot ''Christus'' replica was built out of 30,000 white [[Lego]] pieces by parishioners of a Swedish [[Protestant]] church in [[V\u00e4ster\u00e5s]].<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30178992/ns/world_news-europe/t/swedish-parishioners-unveil-jesus-lego-statue/ |title= Swedish parishioners unveil Jesus Lego statue |publisher= [[NBC News]] |date= 2009-04-12 |agency= [[Associated Press|AP]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131021203615/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30178992/ns/world_news-europe/t/swedish-parishioners-unveil-jesus-lego-statue/ |archivedate= 2013-10-21 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAnother copy of the statue is in front of the [[Friedenskirche]] in [[Potsdam]], which was built from 1845-1854.\n\nAn additional replica of [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]'s Christus statue is found in the church of [[:nb:Sankt Petri kirke|Sankt Petri]] [[Stavanger|Stavanger, Norway]] where it has been on display since 1853.\n\nOne replica is in the Koranda Congregation Chapel of the [[Evangelical Church of Czech Brethren]] in the Czech city of [[Plze\u0148|Pilsen]].\n\nOne replica is at St. John United Lutheran Church in Seattle, Washington, USA.  This church was originally a Danish speaking Lutheran Church.\n\nOne replica is at St. Paul's United Methodist Church in Houston, Texas, USA.\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Christus (Draft) by Thorvaldsen.jpg|A draft of ''Christus'' by Thorvaldsen, located in the Thorvaldsen Museum, Copenhagen.\nFile:SLC replica of the Christus.jpg|Replica at [[Temple Square]], Salt Lake City, Utah.\nFile:Christ JHM.jpg|Replica at [[The Johns Hopkins Hospital]] at Baltimore, Maryland.\nFile:Luisenfriedhof I - Christus Grab Haesel und Zeidler.jpg|Bronze replica at Luisenfriedhof I cemetery in Berlin.\nFile:Luisenfriedhof III - Grab Kummerl\u00e9, Skulptur.jpg|Replica at [[Luisenfriedhof III]] cemetery in Berlin.\nFile:Haggenmacher-s%C3%ADr.jpg|A 1919 replica created for the [[Henrik_Haggenmacher|Haggenmacher]] family tomb at the [[Farkasr\u00e9ti Cemetery]] in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]].\nFile:Church of Peace HDR-crop.jpg|Replica at [[Church of Peace (Sanssouci)|Church of Peace]] in the palace grounds of [[Sanssouci Park]] in [[Potsdam]], Germany\nFile:Skt Petri Kirke, Stavanger-crop.jpg|Replica found in Sankt Petri Stavanger, Norway\n</gallery>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Thorvaldsen's Christus|Thorvaldsen's ''Christus''}}\n\n{{coord|55|40|46|N|12|34|23|E|type:landmark_region:DK-101|display=title}}\n\n{{Bertel Thorvaldsen}}\n[[Category:1821 sculptures]]\n[[Category:Latter Day Saint art]]\n[[Category:Marble sculptures in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Sculptures by Bertel Thorvaldsen]]\n[[Category:Statues of Jesus]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the statue of Jesus in Indianapolis, Indiana|Christus (Indianapolis)}}\n{{italic title}}\n[[File:Thorvaldsen Christus.jpg|thumb|200px|The original statue at the [[Church of Our Lady (Copenhagen)|Church of Our Lady]], [[Copenhagen]].]]\n'''''Christus''''' (also known as '''''Christus Consolator''''') is a 19th-century [[Carrara marble]] statue of the [[resurrection of Jesus|resurrected]] [[Jesus]] by [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]. Since its completion in 1838, the statue has been located in the [[Church of Denmark|Evangelical Lutheran Church in Denmark]]'s [[Church of Our Lady (Copenhagen)|Church of Our Lady]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. In the 20th century, images and replicas of the statue were adopted by the leaders of [[The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints]] (LDS Church) to emphasize the centrality of Jesus Christ in church teachings.\n\n==Original sculpture==\nThorvaldsen was commissioned to sculpt statues of Jesus and the apostles for the [[Church of Our Lady (Copenhagen)|Church of Our Lady]] in Copenhagen. The statue of Jesus was completed in 1821.The statue is 345 centimeter high.<ref>{{cite book |title=Billeder og billedkunst |last=Villadsen |first=Ole |authorlink= |coauthors= |year= |publisher=Gyldendal |location= |isbn= 87-00-33896-6|page=102|pages= |url= |accessdate=}}</ref> The inscription at the base of the sculpture reads \"Kommer til mig\" (\"Come to me\") with a reference to the Bible verse: [[Matthew 11:28]].\n\nThe ''Christus'' was not well known outside of Denmark until 1896, when an American textbook writer wrote that the statue was \"considered the most perfect statue of Christ in the world.\"<ref>{{cite book |last= Coe |first= Fanny E. |editor-last= Dunton |editor-first= Larkin |title= Modern Europe |url= https://archive.org/details/worldanditspeop01duntgoog |place= Boston |publisher= [[Silver Burdett]] |series= The Young Folks' Library '''9''', The World and Its People '''5''' |year= 1896 |page = [https://archive.org/stream/worldanditspeop01duntgoog#page/n132/mode/1up 126] |oclc= 14865981 }}</ref>{{Primary source inline|reason=Cited work is a primary document and cannot justify the claim.|date=December 2019}}{{dubious|Not known outside Denmark?||date=December 2019}}\n\n==Use by the LDS Church==\nIn the 1950s, [[Stephen L Richards]], a church [[Apostle (LDS Church)|apostle]], purchased a 3.4-metre (11-foot) replica of the ''Christus'' and presented it to [[President of the Church (LDS Church)|church president]] [[David O. McKay]]. In 1966, the statue was placed at the church's [[Temple Square]] in [[Salt Lake City, Utah]]. The church's second ''Christus'' replica was created to be displayed in its pavilion at the [[1964 New York World's Fair]]. The display of the replica \"was intended to help visitors understand that Latter-day Saints are Christians\".<ref name = EOM>{{citation |authorlink= Florence S. Jacobsen |first= Florence S. |last= Jacobsen |contribution= Christus Statue |contribution-url= http://contentdm.lib.byu.edu/cdm/ref/collection/EoM/id/5596 |pages= 273\u2013274 |editor1-last= Ludlow |editor1-first= Daniel H |editor1-link= Daniel H. Ludlow |title= [[Encyclopedia of Mormonism]] |location= New York |publisher= [[Macmillan Publishing]] |year= 1992 |isbn= 0-02-879602-0 |oclc= 24502140}}</ref>\n\nSince the display of the ''Christus'' at the World's Fair and at Temple Square, the church has created replicas of the statue and displayed them in visitors' centers near [[Temple (LDS Church)|LDS temples]] in [[Hamilton New Zealand Temple|Hamilton, New Zealand]]; [[Laie Hawaii Temple|Laie, Hawaii]]; [[Los Angeles California Temple|Los Angeles, California]]; [[Mesa Arizona Temple|Mesa, Arizona]]; [[Mexico City Mexico Temple|Mexico City]]; [[Nauvoo Illinois Temple|Nauvoo, Illinois]]; [[Oakland California Temple|Oakland, California]]; [[Palmyra New York Temple|Palmyra, New York]]; [[London England Temple|London, England]]; [[Portland Oregon Temple|Portland, Oregon]]; [[Rome Italy Temple|Rome, Italy]]; [[St. George Utah Temple|St. George, Utah]]; [[Washington D.C. Temple|Washington, D.C.]]; [[Paris France Temple|Paris, France]]; [[S\u00e3o Paulo Brazil Temple|S\u00e3o Paulo, Brazil]]; and [[Provo City Center Temple|Provo, Utah]].<ref name = EOM/><ref name = Richardson>{{citation |authorlink= Matthew O. Richardson |first= Matthew O. |last= Richardson |url= http://ldsliving.com/story/4910-the-ichristusi-legacy |title= The ''Christus'' Legacy |journal= [[Deseret Book|LDS Living Magazine]] |date= February 29, 2008 |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20140513011608/http://ldsliving.com/story/4910-the-ichristusi-legacy |archivedate= 2014-05-13 |url-status= live }}. Excerpted from: {{citation |last= Richardson |first= Matthew O.  |title= The Christus Legacy |place= Sandy, Utah |publisher= Leatherwood Press |year= 2007 |isbn= 978-1599920405 |oclc= 157000118 }}</ref> Replicas are also on display at the church's visitors' centers at the [[Hill Cumorah]] and in [[Independence, Missouri]].<ref name = Richardson/> The church uses the image of the ''Christus'' on its webpages and in other official publications<ref name = Richardson/>\n\nOn April 4, 2020, [[Russell M. Nelson]] announced a new symbol to be used, which has an image of the Christus as a central element along with the church's name.<ref>{{citation |url= https://newsroom.churchofjesuschrist.org/article/new-symbol-church-of-jesus-christ |title= [[The Church\u2019s New Symbol Emphasizes the Centrality of the Savior]]}}</ref>\n\n==Other replicas==\nA full-size replica of the ''Christus'' is located in [[The Johns Hopkins Hospital]] in [[Baltimore, Maryland]]; the hospital refers to the statue as ''Christus Consolator''.<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/dome/0312/feature.cfm |title= A Provocative Icon |journal= Dome |volume= 54 |issue= 10 |page= 1 |first= Lindsay |last= Roylance |date= December 2003 |publisher= [[Johns Hopkins Medicine]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131203051048/http://www.hopkinsmedicine.org/dome/0312/feature.cfm |archivedate= 2013-12-03 |url-status= dead }}</ref>\n\nA replica is located at [[Forest Lawn Memorial Park (Glendale)|Forest Lawn Memorial Park]] in Glendale, California in \"The Court of the Christus\" on Cathedral Drive.<ref>http://www.davidrumsey.com/luna/servlet/detail/RUMSEY~8~1~263065~5524046:Pictorial-Map-and-Visitor-s-Guide-t</ref>\n\nIn 2009, a six-foot ''Christus'' replica was built out of 30,000 white [[Lego]] pieces by parishioners of a Swedish [[Protestant]] church in [[V\u00e4ster\u00e5s]].<ref>{{citation |url= http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30178992/ns/world_news-europe/t/swedish-parishioners-unveil-jesus-lego-statue/ |title= Swedish parishioners unveil Jesus Lego statue |publisher= [[NBC News]] |date= 2009-04-12 |agency= [[Associated Press|AP]] |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20131021203615/http://www.nbcnews.com/id/30178992/ns/world_news-europe/t/swedish-parishioners-unveil-jesus-lego-statue/ |archivedate= 2013-10-21 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAnother copy of the statue is in front of the [[Friedenskirche]] in [[Potsdam]], which was built from 1845-1854.\n\nAn additional replica of [[Bertel Thorvaldsen]]'s Christus statue is found in the church of [[:nb:Sankt Petri kirke|Sankt Petri]] [[Stavanger|Stavanger, Norway]] where it has been on display since 1853.\n\nOne replica is in the Koranda Congregation Chapel of the [[Evangelical Church of Czech Brethren]] in the Czech city of [[Plze\u0148|Pilsen]].\n\nOne replica is at St. John United Lutheran Church in Seattle, Washington, USA.  This church was originally a Danish speaking Lutheran Church.\n\nOne replica is at St. Paul's United Methodist Church in Houston, Texas, USA.\n\n==Image gallery==\n<gallery widths=\"px\" heights=\"160px\">\nFile:Christus (Draft) by Thorvaldsen.jpg|A draft of ''Christus'' by Thorvaldsen, located in the Thorvaldsen Museum, Copenhagen.\nFile:SLC replica of the Christus.jpg|Replica at [[Temple Square]], Salt Lake City, Utah.\nFile:Christ JHM.jpg|Replica at [[The Johns Hopkins Hospital]] at Baltimore, Maryland.\nFile:Luisenfriedhof I - Christus Grab Haesel und Zeidler.jpg|Bronze replica at Luisenfriedhof I cemetery in Berlin.\nFile:Luisenfriedhof III - Grab Kummerl\u00e9, Skulptur.jpg|Replica at [[Luisenfriedhof III]] cemetery in Berlin.\nFile:Haggenmacher-s%C3%ADr.jpg|A 1919 replica created for the [[Henrik_Haggenmacher|Haggenmacher]] family tomb at the [[Farkasr\u00e9ti Cemetery]] in [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]].\nFile:Church of Peace HDR-crop.jpg|Replica at [[Church of Peace (Sanssouci)|Church of Peace]] in the palace grounds of [[Sanssouci Park]] in [[Potsdam]], Germany\nFile:Skt Petri Kirke, Stavanger-cr