{"title_page": "Heliconia excelsa", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|status = VU\n|status_system = IUCN3.1\n|status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n|genus = Heliconia\n|species = excelsa\n|authority = [[Lennart Andersson (botanist)|L.Andersson]]\n}}\n\n'''''Heliconia excelsa''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Heliconiaceae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Ecuador]].<ref>Andersson, Lennart. 1985.  Flora of Ecuador 22: 64\u201365, f. 12B, t. 4.</ref><ref>[http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=248384 Kew World  Checklist of Selected Plant Families, ''Heliconia excelsa'']</ref>  Its natural [[habitat]] is [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]].<ref name=iucn>Ulloa Ulloa, C. & Pitman, N. 2004.  [https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/45380/all ''Heliconia excelsa''].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627000000/http://www.iucnredlist.org/ |date=2014-06-27 }}  Downloaded on 21 August 2007.</ref><ref>Le\u00f3n Y\u00e1nez, S., R. Valencia Reyes, N. C. A. Pitman, L. Endara, C. Ulloa Ulloa & H. Navarrete. 2011. Libro Rojo de las Plantas End\u00e9micas del Ecuador, 2\u00aa edici\u00f3n 1\u2013957. Herbario QCA, Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica del Ecuador, Quito.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5705108}}\n\n[[Category:Flora of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Heliconia|excelsa]]\n[[Category:Vulnerable plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Zingiberales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|status = VU\n|status_system = IUCN3.1\n|status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n|genus = Heliconia\n|species = excelsa\n|authority = [[Lennart Andersson (botanist)|L.Andersson]]\n}}\n\n'''''Heliconia excelsa''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the [[Heliconiaceae]] family. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Ecuador]].<ref>Andersson, Lennart. 1985.  Flora of Ecuador 22: 64\u201365, f. 12B, t. 4.</ref><ref>[http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/namedetail.do?name_id=248384 Kew World  Checklist of Selected Plant Families, ''Heliconia excelsa'']</ref>  Its natural [[habitat]] is subtropical or tropical moist lowland [[forest]]s.<ref name=iucn>Ulloa Ulloa, C. & Pitman, N. 2004.  [http://www.iucnredlist.org/search/details.php/45380/all ''Heliconia excelsa''].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140627000000/http://www.iucnredlist.org/ |date=2014-06-27 }}  Downloaded on 21 August 2007.</ref><ref>Le\u00f3n Y\u00e1nez, S., R. Valencia Reyes, N. C. A. Pitman, L. Endara, C. Ulloa Ulloa & H. Navarrete. 2011. Libro Rojo de las Plantas End\u00e9micas del Ecuador, 2\u00aa edici\u00f3n 1\u2013957. Herbario QCA, Pontificia Universidad Cat\u00f3lica del Ecuador, Quito.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q5705108}}\n\n[[Category:Flora of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Heliconia|excelsa]]\n[[Category:Vulnerable plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Zingiberales-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heliconia_excelsa"}
{"title_page": "Heliconia virginalis", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|status = VU\n|status_system = IUCN3.1\n|status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n|genus = Heliconia\n|species = virginalis\n|authority = [[Jos\u00e9 E. Abalo|Abalo]] & [[Gustavo Morales L.|G.L.Morales]]\n}}\n\n'''''Heliconia virginalis''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Heliconiaceae]].<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13158863#page/428/mode/1up Jos\u00e9 E. Abalo & Gustavo Morales L. 1983.  Phytologia 52(6): 410-411, f. sn., ''Heliconia virginalis'']</ref> It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Ecuador]].<ref>http [http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/furtherInformation.do?name_id=248657 Kew World Checklist of Selected Plant Families, ''Heliconia virginalis'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=iucn>Ulloa Ulloa, C. & Pitman, N. 2004.  [https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/45394/all ''Heliconia virginalis''].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ]  Downloaded on 21 August 2007.</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3926834}}\n\n[[Category:Heliconia|virginalis]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Vulnerable plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Zingiberales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|status = VU\n|status_system = IUCN3.1\n|status_ref = <ref name=iucn/>\n|genus = Heliconia\n|species = virginalis\n|authority = [[Jos\u00e9 E. Abalo|Abalo]] & [[Gustavo Morales L.|G.L.Morales]]\n}}\n\n'''''Heliconia virginalis''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the [[Heliconiaceae]] family.<ref>[https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13158863#page/428/mode/1up Jos\u00e9 E. Abalo & Gustavo Morales L. 1983.  Phytologia 52(6): 410-411, f. sn., ''Heliconia virginalis'']</ref> It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Ecuador]].<ref>http [http://apps.kew.org/wcsp/furtherInformation.do?name_id=248657 Kew World Checklist of Selected Plant Families, ''Heliconia virginalis'']</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|refs=\n<ref name=iucn>Ulloa Ulloa, C. & Pitman, N. 2004.  [http://www.iucnredlist.org/search/details.php/45394/all ''Heliconia virginalis''].   [http://www.iucnredlist.org 2006 IUCN Red List of Threatened Species. ]  Downloaded on 21 August 2007.</ref>\n}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3926834}}\n\n[[Category:Heliconia|virginalis]]\n[[Category:Endemic flora of Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Vulnerable plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Zingiberales-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heliconia_virginalis"}
{"title_page": "Heliconia angusta", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Heliconia angusta.jpg\n|genus = Heliconia\n|species = angusta\n|authority = Vell.\n}}\n\n'''''Heliconia angusta''''' Vell. ([[synonymy|syn.]]: ''Heliconia agustifolia'' Hook., ''Heliconia bicolor'' Benth., ''Heliconia brasiliensis'' Hook.), of family [[Heliconiaceae]] is an erect herb typically growing  0.70 m tall, native to [[Brazil]] ([[South America]]).\n\n==General==\n''Heliconia angusta'' is commonly called the Christmas heliconia because its red and white inflorescences usually emerge during the holiday season. Wild populations, native to southeastern Brazil, are classified as vulnerable by the World Conservation Union largely due to the conversion of their diminishing habitats for agricultural purposes. However, the genetic diversity of wild populations has, at least in part, been preserved by the ex-situ cultivation of ''Heliconia angusta''. The popularity of ''Heliconia angusta'' as a tropical garden plant and horticultural specimen has encouraged widespread propagation of this species by commercial nurseries and botanical gardens.<ref>1</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nIt is a popular [[ornamental plant]] in subtropical  regions with a humid climate. The most cold hardy of ''Heliconia'', it is grown with success in warm temperate climates.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{in lang|pt}} Lorenzi, H.; Souza, M.S. (2001) ''Plantas Ornamentais no Brasil: arbustivas, herb\u00e1ceas e trepadeiras.'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20190101225909/http://www.plantarum.com.br/ Plantarum] {{ISBN|85-86714-12-7}}\n* {{in lang|pt}} [http://www.usbg.gov/plant-collections/conservation/Heliconia-angusta.cfm]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2727848}}\n\n[[Category:Heliconia|angusta]]\n[[Category:Flora of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{Zingiberales-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n|image = Heliconia angusta.jpg\n|genus = Heliconia\n|species = angusta\n|authority = Vell.\n}}\n\n'''''Heliconia angusta''''' Vell. ([[synonymy|syn.]]: ''Heliconia agustifolia'' Hook., ''Heliconia bicolor'' Benth., ''Heliconia brasiliensis'' Hook.), of [[Heliconiaceae]] family is an erect herb typically growing  0.70 m tall, native to [[Brazil]] ([[South America]]).\n\n==General==\n''Heliconia angusta'' is commonly called the Christmas heliconia because its red and white inflorescences usually emerge during the holiday season. Wild populations, which are native to southeastern Brazil, are classified as vulnerable by the World Conservation Union largely due to the conversion of their diminishing habitats for agricultural purposes. However, the genetic diversity of wild populations has, at least in part, been preserved by the ex-situ cultivation of ''Heliconia angusta''. The popularity of ''Heliconia angusta'' as a tropical garden plant and horticultural specimen has encouraged widespread propagation of this species by commercial nurseries and botanical gardens.<ref>1</ref>\n\n==Uses==\nIt is a popular [[ornamental plant]] in subtropical  regions with a humid climate. The most cold hardy of ''Heliconia'', it is grown with success in warm temperate climates.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* {{in lang|pt}} Lorenzi, H.; Souza, M.S. (2001) ''Plantas Ornamentais no Brasil: arbustivas, herb\u00e1ceas e trepadeiras.'' [https://web.archive.org/web/20190101225909/http://www.plantarum.com.br/ Plantarum] {{ISBN|85-86714-12-7}}\n* {{in lang|pt}} [http://www.usbg.gov/plant-collections/conservation/Heliconia-angusta.cfm]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q2727848}}\n\n[[Category:Heliconia|angusta]]\n[[Category:Flora of Brazil]]\n\n\n{{Zingiberales-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heliconia_angusta"}
{"title_page": "Patrick Walsh (investor)", "text_new": "'''Patrick Walsh''' (born December 26, 1975) is an entrepreneur and investor in the United States. He is the founder and CEO of PW Partners, LLC, an investment management firm.  Walsh is also the Chairman and Chief Executive of [[Town Sports International]], a holding company that trades on the NASDAQ under the symbol CLUB.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/commercial-clubs/town-sports-names-patrick-walsh-ceo-consolidates-coo-role|title=Town Sports Names Patrick Walsh CEO, Consolidates COO Role|date=2017-05-04|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>  Walsh is also a member of the Board of Directors of [[BJ's Restaurants]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investors.bjsrestaurants.com/board-member/patrick-walsh|title=Patrick Walsh {{!}} Board Member {{!}} BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|website=BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|language=en|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> and [[Del Taco Restaurants]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalsh was born in San Diego, California, the eldest of three brothers.  His father was in the [[U.S. Navy]] and his mother was a school teacher. \n[[File:Patrick Walsh .jpg|thumb|Patrick Walsh the 2018 EY Entrepreneur of the Year award winner in the New York region.]]\nThe Walsh family left California and moved to Boston, Massachusetts in 1977 and Walsh grew up in [[Foxboro, Massachusetts]], the home of the [[New England Patriots]]. Walsh remains a die-hard Patriots fan to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/get-your-mind-right-with-boston-sports-clubs-and-gronk-fitness-300378152.html|title=Get Your Mind Right with Boston Sports Clubs and Gronk Fitness|last=Clubs|first=Boston Sports|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref> Walsh studied economics at [[Wesleyan University]] and played football and baseball<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/bsb/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_bbf0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/fball/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_0ml0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> until he suffered a severe back injury playing football. He transferred to [[Boston College]] after his freshman year and graduated with a degree in accounting. After graduation, he earned the [[Chartered Financial Analyst]] designation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly in his career, Walsh rejected the academic [[efficient-market theory]] and adhered instead to a philosophy of [[value investing]]. Walsh enrolled in the Value Investing Executive Program at [[Columbia Business School]] to study under Professor [[Bruce Greenwald]], who carried on the teachings (albeit evolved) of [[Benjamin Graham]], the father of value investing.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n<ref></ref>==Early business career==\nWalsh worked from 1998 to 2004 at Prudential Capital Group and Prudential Securities in real estate private equity and equity research; from 2004 to 2008 at Deutsche Bank as an investment banker and at a private hedge fund based in Chicago from 2008 to 2011.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bjs-restaurants-shareholders-come-to-board-agreement-1398172042|title=BJ's Restaurants, Shareholders Come to Board Agreement|last=McCarthy|first=Erin|date=2014-04-22|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nWalsh formed the predecessor to PW Partners, LLC in October 2011.  During Walsh's tenure in the hedge fund industry and at PW Partners he practiced corporate activism while investing in Denny's,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/04/15/dennys-slams-investors-leading-proxy-fight/|title=Denny's Slams Investors Leading Proxy Fight|last=Dealbook|work=DealBook|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> Red Robin Gourmet Burgers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110124005491/en/Oak-Street-Capital-Management-LLC-Addresses-Board|title=Oak Street Capital Management, LLC Addresses the Board of Red Robin Gourmet Burgers|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> Great Wolf Resorts,<ref name=\":1\" /> Famous Dave's,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/July-2015/Finally-Board-Diversity-at-Famous-Daves/|title=Finally, Board Diversity at Famous Dave\u2019s - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - July 2015|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> BJ's Restaurants<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/17/activist-investing-wont-save-this-company.aspx|title=Activist Investing Won't Save This Company|last=Quast|first=Jon|work=The Motley Fool|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> and Del Taco Restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> A 2014 article in Restaurant Finance Monitor stated that \"each of the chains with which he has become involved have thrived on Wall Street in his wake.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/March-2014/Activist-Bug-Bites-BJs-Restaurants/|title=Activist Bug Bites BJ's Restaurants - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - March 2014|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\nWalsh invested in Town Sports International and claimed that the fitness business had been his worst investment.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/antoinegara/2015/07/29/patrick-walsh-dennys-red-robin-bjs-restaurants-new-york-sports-clubs/#314f5b001d93|title=Meet Patrick Walsh, The Do-It-Yourself Hedge Fund Activist You've Never Heard Of|last=Gara|first=Antoine|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Town Sports International Holdings'''\n\nIn June 2015 Walsh was named Chairman of the Board of Town Sports International Holdings. The Company was burning $5 million a month and was in the midst of 17 consecutive quarters of same-store sales declines.  The Company was burdened with $300 million of debt that could not be repaid with the current levels of cash flow. This led Moody's rating agency to describe Town's capital structure as \"untenable\" and they downgraded the debt to a \"Caa2\" rating. The stock price declined to 92 cents per share while the Company's debt traded down to 36 cents on the dollar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-downgrades-Town-Sports-CFR-to-Caa2-outlook-negative--PR_343821|title=Moody's downgrades Town Sports' CFR to Caa2; outlook negative|date=2016-02-16|work=Moodys.com|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> In September 2016 Walsh became Chief Executive Officer.<ref name=\":0\" /> While industry experts predicted bankruptcy or a sale,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/03/06/nysc-owner-seeks-a-sale-but-alls-not-gym-dandy/|title=NYSC owner seeks a sale, but all\u2019s not gym-dandy|date=2015-03-07|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Walsh vowed to Town's shareholders that he would never give up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townsportsinternational.com/static-files/da8171a6-e2e2-4cda-b82a-f2296531c66d|title=Letter from the Chairman 2015}}</ref> After 17 consecutive quarters of declines in same store sales the company then posted 5 consecutive quarters of same-store sales increases and the stock price increased more than 1,000% to $11 per share in 2018.\n\nTown Sports International started to make acquisitions in September 2017 acquiring the Lucille Roberts brand, an all woman's fitness chain.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-acquire-lucille-roberts-health-club-business|title=Town Sports International to Acquire Lucille Roberts Health Club Business|date=2017-07-14|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> In December 2017, Town acquired the luxury brand TMPL <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://cheddar.com/videos/building-a-tmpl-to-fitness-with-town-sports-international|title=Building a \"TMPL\" to Fitness with Town Sports International|website=Cheddar|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> and in early 2018 the Company acquired Total Woman, an all woman's fitness chain based in California.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/rlh-equity-partners-portfolio-company-total-woman-acquired-by-town-sports-international-300631093.html|title=RLH Equity Partners portfolio company, Total Woman, acquired by Town Sports International|last=Partners|first=Riordan, Lewis &amp; Haden {{!}} Equity|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Since taking over as CEO Walsh has overseen acquisitions of more than 30 clubs.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-reports-8-million-increase-q1-2018-revenue|title=Town Sports International Reports $8 Million Increase in Q1 2018 Revenue|date=2018-04-30|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nWalsh's writings include his annual letters to shareholders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townsportsinternational.com/corporate-governance/letter-from-the-chairman|title=Letters From the Chairman {{!}} Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|website=Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Walsh was chosen as an [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]]s 2018 New York Finalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/us/en/about-us/entrepreneurship/entrepreneur-of-the-year/met-ny_article_regional_finalists|title=Meet the 2018 Finalists}}</ref> On June 12, 2018 Walsh was selected as the winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ey-announces-winners-for-the-entrepreneur-of-the-year-2018-new-york-award-300665597.html|title=EY Announces Winners for the Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2018 New York Award|last=EY|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\nAs of March 2019 Town Sports International is having problems with their asset New York Sports Club of freezing customers' membership while their gyms are closed because of the Cornavirus.\n\n==References==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:CFA charterholders]]\n", "text_old": "'''Patrick Walsh''' (born December 26, 1975) is an entrepreneur and investor in the United States. He is the founder and CEO of PW Partners, LLC, an investment management firm.  Walsh is also the Chairman and Chief Executive of [[Town Sports International]], a holding company that trades on the NASDAQ under the symbol CLUB.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/commercial-clubs/town-sports-names-patrick-walsh-ceo-consolidates-coo-role|title=Town Sports Names Patrick Walsh CEO, Consolidates COO Role|date=2017-05-04|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>  Walsh is also a member of the Board of Directors of [[BJ's Restaurants]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investors.bjsrestaurants.com/board-member/patrick-walsh|title=Patrick Walsh {{!}} Board Member {{!}} BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|website=BJ's Restaurants, Inc.|language=en|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref> and [[Del Taco Restaurants]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-05-31}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nWalsh was born in San Diego, California, the eldest of three brothers.  His father was in the [[U.S. Navy]] and his mother was a school teacher. \n[[File:Patrick Walsh .jpg|thumb|Patrick Walsh the 2018 EY Entrepreneur of the Year award winner in the New York region.]]\nThe Walsh family left California and moved to Boston, Massachusetts in 1977 and Walsh grew up in [[Foxboro, Massachusetts]], the home of the [[New England Patriots]]. Walsh remains a die-hard Patriots fan to this day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/get-your-mind-right-with-boston-sports-clubs-and-gronk-fitness-300378152.html|title=Get Your Mind Right with Boston Sports Clubs and Gronk Fitness|last=Clubs|first=Boston Sports|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref> Walsh studied economics at [[Wesleyan University]] and played football and baseball<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/bsb/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_bbf0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://athletics.wesleyan.edu/sports/fball/1994-95/bios/walsh_pat_0ml0|title=Pat Walsh|website=Wesleyan Athletics|language=en|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref> until he suffered a severe back injury playing football. He transferred to [[Boston College]] after his freshman year and graduated with a degree in accounting. After graduation, he earned the [[Chartered Financial Analyst]] designation.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nEarly in his career, Walsh rejected the academic [[efficient-market theory]] and adhered instead to a philosophy of [[value investing]]. Walsh enrolled in the Value Investing Executive Program at [[Columbia Business School]] to study under Professor [[Bruce Greenwald]], who carried on the teachings (albeit evolved) of [[Benjamin Graham]], the father of value investing.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Early business career==\nWalsh worked from 1998 to 2004 at Prudential Capital Group and Prudential Securities in real estate private equity and equity research; from 2004 to 2008 at Deutsche Bank as an investment banker and at a private hedge fund based in Chicago from 2008 to 2011.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/bjs-restaurants-shareholders-come-to-board-agreement-1398172042|title=BJ's Restaurants, Shareholders Come to Board Agreement|last=McCarthy|first=Erin|date=2014-04-22|work=Wall Street Journal|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US|issn=0099-9660}}</ref>\n\nWalsh formed the predecessor to PW Partners, LLC in October 2011.  During Walsh's tenure in the hedge fund industry and at PW Partners he practiced corporate activism while investing in Denny's,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2010/04/15/dennys-slams-investors-leading-proxy-fight/|title=Denny's Slams Investors Leading Proxy Fight|last=Dealbook|work=DealBook|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> Red Robin Gourmet Burgers,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20110124005491/en/Oak-Street-Capital-Management-LLC-Addresses-Board|title=Oak Street Capital Management, LLC Addresses the Board of Red Robin Gourmet Burgers|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> Great Wolf Resorts,<ref name=\":1\" /> Famous Dave's,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/July-2015/Finally-Board-Diversity-at-Famous-Daves/|title=Finally, Board Diversity at Famous Dave\u2019s - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - July 2015|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> BJ's Restaurants<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.fool.com/investing/general/2014/03/17/activist-investing-wont-save-this-company.aspx|title=Activist Investing Won't Save This Company|last=Quast|first=Jon|work=The Motley Fool|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> and Del Taco Restaurants.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://investor.deltaco.com/corporate-governance/board-of-directors/default.aspx|title=Del Taco Restaurants, Inc. - Corporate Governance - Board of Directors|website=investor.deltaco.com|language=en-CA|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref> A 2014 article in Restaurant Finance Monitor stated that \"each of the chains with which he has become involved have thrived on Wall Street in his wake.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.restfinance.com/Restaurant-Finance-Across-America/March-2014/Activist-Bug-Bites-BJs-Restaurants/|title=Activist Bug Bites BJ's Restaurants - Restaurant Industry Insight and Analysis - March 2014|website=www.restfinance.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\nWalsh invested in Town Sports International and claimed that the fitness business had been his worst investment.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/antoinegara/2015/07/29/patrick-walsh-dennys-red-robin-bjs-restaurants-new-york-sports-clubs/#314f5b001d93|title=Meet Patrick Walsh, The Do-It-Yourself Hedge Fund Activist You've Never Heard Of|last=Gara|first=Antoine|work=Forbes|access-date=2018-05-07|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''Town Sports International Holdings'''\n\nIn June 2015 Walsh was named Chairman of the Board of Town Sports International Holdings. The Company was burning $5 million a month and was in the midst of 17 consecutive quarters of same-store sales declines.  The Company was burdened with $300 million of debt that could not be repaid with the current levels of cash flow. This led Moody's rating agency to describe Town's capital structure as \"untenable\" and they downgraded the debt to a \"Caa2\" rating. The stock price declined to 92 cents per share while the Company's debt traded down to 36 cents on the dollar.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.moodys.com/research/Moodys-downgrades-Town-Sports-CFR-to-Caa2-outlook-negative--PR_343821|title=Moody's downgrades Town Sports' CFR to Caa2; outlook negative|date=2016-02-16|work=Moodys.com|access-date=2018-06-14}}</ref> In September 2016 Walsh became Chief Executive Officer.<ref name=\":0\" /> While industry experts predicted bankruptcy or a sale,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://nypost.com/2015/03/06/nysc-owner-seeks-a-sale-but-alls-not-gym-dandy/|title=NYSC owner seeks a sale, but all\u2019s not gym-dandy|date=2015-03-07|work=New York Post|access-date=2018-05-11|language=en-US}}</ref> Walsh vowed to Town's shareholders that he would never give up.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.townsportsinternational.com/static-files/da8171a6-e2e2-4cda-b82a-f2296531c66d|title=Letter from the Chairman 2015}}</ref> After 17 consecutive quarters of declines in same store sales the company then posted 5 consecutive quarters of same-store sales increases and the stock price increased more than 1,000% to $11 per share in 2018.\n\nTown Sports International started to make acquisitions in September 2017 acquiring the Lucille Roberts brand, an all woman's fitness chain.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-acquire-lucille-roberts-health-club-business|title=Town Sports International to Acquire Lucille Roberts Health Club Business|date=2017-07-14|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> In December 2017, Town acquired the luxury brand TMPL <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://cheddar.com/videos/building-a-tmpl-to-fitness-with-town-sports-international|title=Building a \"TMPL\" to Fitness with Town Sports International|website=Cheddar|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> and in early 2018 the Company acquired Total Woman, an all woman's fitness chain based in California.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/rlh-equity-partners-portfolio-company-total-woman-acquired-by-town-sports-international-300631093.html|title=RLH Equity Partners portfolio company, Total Woman, acquired by Town Sports International|last=Partners|first=Riordan, Lewis &amp; Haden {{!}} Equity|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-07}}</ref> Since taking over as CEO Walsh has overseen acquisitions of more than 30 clubs.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.clubindustry.com/news/town-sports-international-reports-8-million-increase-q1-2018-revenue|title=Town Sports International Reports $8 Million Increase in Q1 2018 Revenue|date=2018-04-30|work=Club Industry|access-date=2018-05-11}}</ref>\n\nWalsh's writings include his annual letters to shareholders.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.townsportsinternational.com/corporate-governance/letter-from-the-chairman|title=Letters From the Chairman {{!}} Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|website=Town Sports International Holdings, Inc.|language=en|access-date=2018-05-15}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Walsh was chosen as an [[Ernst & Young Entrepreneur of the Year Award]]s 2018 New York Finalist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ey.com/us/en/about-us/entrepreneurship/entrepreneur-of-the-year/met-ny_article_regional_finalists|title=Meet the 2018 Finalists}}</ref> On June 12, 2018 Walsh was selected as the winner.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ey-announces-winners-for-the-entrepreneur-of-the-year-2018-new-york-award-300665597.html|title=EY Announces Winners for the Entrepreneur Of The Year\u00ae 2018 New York Award|last=EY|website=www.prnewswire.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-13}}</ref>\nAs of March 2019 Town Sports International is having problems with their asset New York Sports Club of freezing customers' membership while their gyms are closed because of the Cornavirus.\n\n==References==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walsh, Patrick}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from San Diego]]\n[[Category:People from Foxborough, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Wesleyan University alumni]]\n[[Category:Boston College alumni]]\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:CFA charterholders]]\n", "name_user": "Hard44manh", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly business career:ny local news ny1 reports attorney leticia james has warned nysc of taking the gym to task if they don't freeze members accounts.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Walsh_(investor)"}
